<HEAD>Reagan Says Quayle's Debate Effort `Headed Off Picking On'
Candidate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Thursday he believes Republican <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s performance in the vice presidential debate `` headed off, or should have headed off, all this picking on him that has been going on.'' `` I think he handled himself very well,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told reporters who questioned him at a state dinner for President <PERSON> Moussa </PERSON> <PERSON> Traore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>. `` I really think that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> actually, just by the whole nature of the event, headed off, or should have headed off, all this picking on him that has been going on,'' the president said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said that some of the points that the Democrats were claiming were made by <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> in the debate were based on `` things that were not factually true, such as who is responsible for the deficit and so forth.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who is making a campaign trip to <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> on Friday, said he will be picking up the pace of his involvement in the campaign between now and Election Day. Asked whether he thought the issues were being addressed in the campaign, he said, `` Yes, I do. At least by our side.'' Earlier, posing for photographers before a private meeting with <PERSON> Traore </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was asked whether he thought <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> would be damaged by the exchange in which Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> criticized him for comparing himself with the late President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. `` No,'' he said. `` I thought that remark was a cheap shot and unbecoming a senator of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' When asked if it was a mistake for <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> to make the comparison in the first place, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` No. The only comparison he was making was that he was being attacked, I think unfairly, on the basis of his age and his experience in government and he was pointing out that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who sought the highest office and won it, had actually less experience in government than he had and was the same age.''
