<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Kidnappers holding two Americans threatened the hostages' safety Thursday in venting their anger over proposals to send <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> troops to police <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s stalled presidential elections. A Christian militia leader on Thursday called for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> troops in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, a day after <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> suggested the idea. The kidnappers' warning came in a typewritten statement in Arabic from the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The statement was delivered to the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> independent newspaper An-Nahar along with a <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> picture of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hostage <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON>. `` We shall use all the cards to thwart these conspiracies, including the card of the safety of the hostages, which we shall make the backbone of our confrontation,'' the statement said. The photograph showed <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON>, 58, of <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, in a navy blue track suit with red stripes sitting on a blanket-covered bed. His hands were clasped in his lap and he was smiling as he faced the camera, but he looked considerably thinner than in previous pictures released by his captors. <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON> was acting comptroller at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beirut </ORGANIZATION> when he was kidnapped on the school's campus on Sept. 12, 1986. Revolutionary Justice, believed linked to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, also claims to hold <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON>, 57, of <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, an author, who was kidnapped Oct. 21, 1986 in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The note came three days after another group, Islamic Jihad for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, freed <PERSON> Mithileshwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> after 20 months of captivity. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, an Indian professor, is a legal resident of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was kidnapped in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> with three <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> colleagues, who are still captives. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> team is debriefing <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Wiesbaden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and an official close to the team said <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was providing `` a lot of raw information'' that could be helpful in learning about Americans still held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The official spoke on condition of anonymity. The Americans held with <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> are <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, 41, a native of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Alann </PERSON> <PERSON> Steen </PERSON>, 49, of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Polhill </PERSON>, 54, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Sixteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and believed held hostage. The longest held is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985. Thursday's statement from <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON>'s kidnappers denounced `` the rude call for imperialist intervention under the slogan of internationalization by a colonial power whose black history is mothering our present tragedies.'' This appeared to be a reference to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, which proposed this week dispatching a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to oversee election of a new president in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, a former French colony. Two rival Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> governments emerged in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> after <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> failed to elect a new head of state to succeed President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> when his six-year term expired Sept. 22. The communique accused right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> militants of collaborating with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to partition <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> as a first step to turning it into `` an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> satellite and a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> base for intrigues against the people of the region.'' It called the Christian militants `` the grandsons of the crusaders'' and warned: `` We shall mete out the just punishment to the conspirators.'' It was the first communique from <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> since July 7, when the group threatened to `` punish'' hostages for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> downing of an Iranian jetliner over the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Moslems, who make up 55 percent of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 4 million people, have been fighting for an equal share of power in the nation's 13-year-old civil war Christian militia commander <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> on Thursday echoed <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s call for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Christian and Moslem sectors to oversee presidential elections. `` I propose the formation of a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> force to deploy in the greater <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to oversee the presidential election,'' <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> said the plan should include withdrawal of his Lebanese Forces militia from Christian east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, and of Syrian troops and allied leftist and Moslem militiamen from the city's western sector. Asked whether the proposed <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> force should remain after <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> elects a new president, <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> said: `` It is for the new president and the new Cabinet he forms to decide that.''
