<HEAD>The Diamond Is A Studio's Best Friend, At Long Last</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The success of this summer's `` Bull Durham'' has helped lead the way to an outpouring of movies about baseball, once considered box-office poison by the moguls who ran the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> studios. During its first month of release, `` Bull Durham,'' a funny, sexy account of minor-league baseball starring <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarandon </PERSON>, scored $ 26 million in ticket sales in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The Orion release, written and directed by former <PERSON> bush </PERSON> league player <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON>, has been followed by `` Eight Men Out'' and `` Stealing Home.'' `` Eight Men Out,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayles </PERSON>' drama about baseball's greatest scandal, the sellout by members of the 1919 <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION>, received a warm welcome from critics. Stars include <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON>, D.B. <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cusack </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jodie </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> won raves for her performance in `` Stealing Home,'' the story of a minor league ballplayer seeking a comeback after years on the skids. TV's <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> co-stars. Upcoming baseball movies include: _ `` <ORGANIZATION> Major </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>,'' with <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON> as members of a hapless team who suddenly become winners, Rocky-style. _ `` The Scout,'' <PERSON> Anson </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> directing <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Dangerfield </PERSON> as a baseball scout who uncovers a potential superstar. It is filming this fall. _ `` Shoeless <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>,'' filming in <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, with <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Costner </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON>. According to writer-director <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Alden </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, it is not really a baseball movie. Based on a novel by W.P. <PERSON> Kinsella </PERSON>, it concerns a farmer -LRB- <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> -RRB- who is told by a spirit that <PERSON> Shoeless </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> fame will come back to life if he builds a diamond in a cornfield. _ `` Trading Hearts,'' already playing in a few regions, a romance about a pitcher -LRB- <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> -RRB-, who is cut from spring training. Producer <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> said `` Trading Hearts'' also is not a baseball picture. That's a hangover from the long-held belief that baseball strikes out in theaters. The arguments most often heard over the years are that baseball is incomprehensible to foreign audiences, and that women, who make up a large part of movie audiences, will not want to see films about baseball. <PERSON> Thom </PERSON> <PERSON> Mount </PERSON>, producer of `` Bull Durham'' and part owner of the minor league <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bulls </ORGANIZATION>, encountered such prejudice when he sought a releasing company. `` Five studios turned us down before <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> picked up ` <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Durham </ORGANIZATION>,''' he said. `` We were told simply that baseball pictures do n't make money.'' He attributed the film's success to the appeal of <PERSON> Costner </PERSON>. `` Also, young women are impressed with the role <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarandon </PERSON> plays _ a strong, vital, liberated character.'' By attracting the female audience, `` Bull Durham'' appears to have solved one of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s prejudices. It remains to be seen whether it can also appeal to foreign moviegoers; there is hope in baseball-crazy <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and the game has been spreading to other countries as well. Given the reasonable cost _ $ 9 million _ `` <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Durham </ORGANIZATION>'' is assured of a profit in the domestic market alone. A survey of baseball movies over the years indicates that the studios' anti-baseball attitude may have been justified. Even the box-office luster of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> could n't convert the allegorical `` The Natural'' into a winner. The best-remembered of baseball movies, `` The Pride of the <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION>,'' with <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> as <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Gehrig </PERSON>, was another commercial disappointment. Many other biographical films have failed to excite the movie-going public, especially women: `` The Winning Team,'' with <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as <PERSON> Grover </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleveland </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>; `` The Babe <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendix </PERSON> as the great Bambino; `` The <PERSON> Stratton </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> as <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Stratton </PERSON>, who staged a comeback after losing a leg; `` The Pride of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dailey </PERSON> <PE