<HEAD>Acting Is Like Baseball: Just Do It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 D.B. <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> approaches acting the way Shoeless <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> played baseball: Just do it. `` The best theory I ever heard about acting was from -LRB- <PERSON> James </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Cagney </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON>, 26, who plays <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayles </PERSON>' `` Eight Men Out,'' the story of the 1919 <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> scandal `` You walk in. Plant your feet. Stare the other fellow in the eyes and tell the truth. All the acting theories I've heard, all the books I've read ... you ca n't get it any simpler or purer than that.'' `` Eight Men Out'' tells the story of the biggest scandal in baseball. The 1919 White Sox were widely regarded as the best team of their time. With such pitchers as <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicotte </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lefty </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, and a lineup featuring future Hall of Famers <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Schalk </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> won the American League pennant and were heavy favorites against the <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> in the World Series. No one, however, could play ball like <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a lifetime .356 hitter and outstanding left fielder. Once a mill worker in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, he had little education and could not read or write, but was peerless on the field. `` He was very passive,'' <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> noted. `` He took the path of least resistance in everything he could. Everything he did was from a defensive mode, except on the field, where he attacks.'' <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> wanted to contrast <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s athletic grace with his awkwardness in private life. `` On the field, I wanted him to be like -LRB- ballet superstar <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON>. I wanted every move he made to be beautiful,'' <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> said. `` Off the field, I wanted him to be tentative.'' Players earned little money in <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s era and were often tempted by gamblers to throw games. Eight members of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION>, including <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, agreed to, or were aware of, an effort to deliberately throw the series against <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> won the series and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION>' poor play aroused widespread suspicion. The following year, Commissioner <PERSON> Kenesaw </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Landis </PERSON> permanently banned <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and his seven teammates from baseball. No one could ever prove that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who batted .375 in the World Series, ever tried to throw a game. More likely, he was punished for being aware of the fix and not trying to stop it. `` They do n't kick you out of the Pentagon for knowing about fraud,'' <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> said, adding that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who died in 1951, should have his name cleared and be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> was born and raised in <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION>, N.Y. He attended <ORGANIZATION> Tulane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and hoped to play major league baseball until tearing ligaments in his right knee. The injury convinced <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> to pursue a career in acting, and he transferred to the performing arts division of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. After graduating in 1984, he appeared in the Broadway revival of `` The Caine Mutiny.'' He made his film debut in <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Lumet </PERSON>'s `` Power,'' and has since appeared in <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> <PERSON> Coppola </PERSON>'s `` Gardens of Stone'' and `` No Man's Land.'' Although <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> has not appeared on stage in two years, he still prefers the working atmosphere of the theater. `` On ` No Man's Land,' there were about four producers, one director to start the film and one to end it. We had five different writers. And by the way, we also have these actors,'' he said. `` In a play, even if it's a <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> play on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>, it's going to have to be about the actors or nobody's going to come I enjoy acting on stage better because there are less people with walkie-talkie's in your face.'' <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> felt an immediate rapport with <PERSON> Sayles </PERSON> -LRB- `` Brother From Another Planet,'' `` Matewan'' -RRB-, and enjoyed working with him on the set. `` We met in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and talked for about an hour. We talked about <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Clemente </PERSON> -LRB- the late <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> Pirates star -RRB-. <PERSON> John </PERSON> likes the <ORGANIZATION> Pirates </ORGANIZATION>. He's a real blue-collar man. Those are the right reasons to like a baseball team,'' he said. `` I had access to <PERSON> John </PERSON> all the time. We had a great relationship. We would just check in with each other to gauge each other's continued enthusiasm.'' To prepare for the film, <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and worked out with the local minor league team. `` <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> is a good town for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. A real blue-collar town. Everybody there works for one of those corporations. I think there's a similar ethic about work that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> might have grown up with. `` That's the world where <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> came from.'' Playing <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> boiled down to forgetting about everything except baseball. `` I tried to stand there and clear my mind,'' <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> said. `` He would just stand and take his three swings and more often than not, hit it, and hit it well. In my daily life, I have to deal with bank statements, acting, associates and friends and things. It's often like a juggling act.''
