<HEAD>With PM-AP Arts: Baseball Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's so, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>. The baseball movie, long relegated to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s minor leagues, is the winner of 1988's cinematic comeback of the year award. From summer smash `` Bull Durham'' to critical rave `` Eight Men Out,'' baseball movies are back. And so what if `` Stealing Home,'' the Mark Harmon-Jodie Foster entry in the baseball movie race, was almost universally panned? Two out of three means <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> is batting .667 this year. The bounce back of baseball has prompted musings on the subject in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>. Actor <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> delivered the Most Valuable Performance in `` Durham'' as veteran minor league catcher <PERSON> Crash </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, but an assortment of stars suited up this year: <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON> and D.B. <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON>, to name a few. <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON> will do it again for movies coming out next year. The switch-hitting <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> will appear in `` Shoeless <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>,'' playing a farmer under the sway of `` Black Sox'' star <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s ghost, while <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON> will be joined by `` <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> Law'' star <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON> in `` Major League. But why this return of the ballplayer as movie star after years without any horsehide hits? _ The ` R' rating. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> as <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Gehrig </PERSON>, who was married in `` Pride of the <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION