<SECOND>PM-Chinese Ship,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detained Ship Departs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Military authorities allowed a Chinese research ship to sail away today after they were convinced the vessel had simply sought shelter from a typhoon and was not smuggling guns to local communist rebels, officials said. The 3,324-ton Science Research Vessel No. 1 had steamed into northern <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s Casiguran Sound late Monday and <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> Constabulary troops seized it early the next day after a boarding party found guns and ammunition aboard. The <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said the ship was seeking shelter from Typhoon <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, which skirted northern <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> Wednesday, and the arms aboard were for protection of the ship's 56 scientists and 45 crew from pirates. The arms included three machine guns, eight assault rifles, two semi-automatic rifles, two hand guns and 4,850 rounds of ammunition. Maj. <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Yarcia </PERSON>, a constabulary intelligence officer inspected the vessel for a second time Wednesday, and told reporters today he found no signs the ship or the people aboard had violated any Philippine law. The ship's scientists were reportedly aboard to conduct underwater research. Military officials are wary of ships with arms because of frequent reports of smuggling to communist rebels waging a 19-year insurgency. Casiguran is in an area known for years as a rebel stronghold. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> maintains diplomatic relations with the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and has consistently denied giving the rebels any material aid.
