<HEAD>New Ammunition Draws Outcry As Casualties Mount</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Israeli army's use of plastic bullets to break up Palestinian demonstrations is filling hospital wards with casualties and prompting calls for tighter controls. Victims of the new ammunition, including two teen-agers treated for plastic bullet wounds at <LOCATION> Ahli </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, complain that stones thrown by protesters do not warrant the penalty. `` It's unreasonable punishment,'' said <PERSON> Mazul </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lail </PERSON>, 19, a tailor who was shot in the ankle. In a nearby bed, 16-year-old <PERSON> Rifaat </PERSON> <PERSON> Massoud </PERSON>, a construction worker, nodded in agreement. `` It is n't right and it is n't fair for the soldiers to shoot innocent people,'' <PERSON> Massoud </PERSON> said, shifting uncomfortably with a bullet wound in his left side. The plastic bullet was introduced in August to supplement rubber bullets, water cannons, tear gas and clubs in dealing with the uprising in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said the other weapons `` proved to be insufficient to cope with stone throwing'' and that the army needed something less lethal than lead bullets. The aim, <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said, is to reduce anti-Israeli violence in the territories with a minimum of fatalities. Since the uprising began Dec. 8, at least 280 Palestinians have been killed and hundreds injured. Six Israelis have died. But <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> has acknowledged that the introduction of the plastic bullets may lead to more injuries. In the past three weeks, more than 325 Palestinians have been wounded in clashes with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops, many by plastic bullets, hospital officials and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> sources say. The army says plastic bullets can penetrate the body, but they are not supposed to be lethal if fired from at least 70 yards. However, at least four deaths from plastic bullets have been reported at <LOCATION> Shifa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Last week, Dr. <PERSON> Rustum </PERSON> <PERSON> Namari </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> Mukassad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, showed reporters fragments of a plastic bullet removed from the brain of a critically injured <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> youth. <PERSON> Namari </PERSON> said the bullet appeared to have been fired at close range. `` If a plastic bullet enters the throat, chest or abdomen, it has the potential to cause death,'' said a surgeon at <ORGANIZATION> Shifa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> who spoke on condition of anonymnity. `` Remember, too, that bullets respect no age,'' he added. Victims, he said, have ranged in age from 7 to 90. The bullets, developed after <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials studied use of plastic ammunition in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, are produced in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Similar plastic rounds have been used in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> for riot control since 1970, and at least 13 deaths have been attributed to them there. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> have objected to the use of plastic ammunition against <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> demonstrators, and opposition has been mounting in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. A senior official of the U.N. Relief and <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, which provides humanitarian services to Palestinian refugees, filed a complaint with Israeli military officials after casualties in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> jumped from 19 in July to more than 130 in September. Last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> filed a petition with Israeli Attorney General <PERSON> Yosef </PERSON> <PERSON> Harish </PERSON>, urging him to issue legal guidelines on the use of the new bullets. The group contended that `` opening fire for purposes of deterrence is an illegal act'' and called on <PERSON> Harish </PERSON> to block use of the bullet for riot control. Until recently, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers were instructed to fire lead or plastic bullets only if their lives were in imminent danger. In recent weeks, however, firing rules have been changed so troops may use the plastic rounds to break up demonstrations. The army chief of staff, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON>, told a parliament committee Tuesday that the army needed to stop riots before they get out of hand. `` Arabs who deliberately choose to go out and demonstrate are getting injured,'' <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON> was quoted as saying in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> newspapers. `` Eventually they will realize that it is not in their interest to get involved in riots.'' But he insisted strict orders had been issued against misusing the new weapon. In addition to a firing range of 70 yards, the bullets are to be aimed only at legs, <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON> said.
