<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In just six months, Italian fashion has experienced a radical mood swing from aggressive and sexy to subdued and demure. Leaving the miniskirted, spike-heeled woman behind, the Italian designers presenting their spring-summer 1989 collections in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> this week are courting a younger, at least outwardly more innocent woman who loves pants, long skirts and flat shoes. Her favorite colors are tender shades of cream and pink or the classic combination of white with navy blue or black. Her taste in fabrics ranges from diaphanous georgette and chiffon to batiste and linen. Crisp white blouses, always a sign of good clean living, pop up throughout the collections. Some are man-tailored, others daintily lace-collared, still others a feminine version of the bowling shirt. <PERSON> Gianfranco </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s `` numero uno'' shirtmaker, opts for a wide collared, man-tailored silk shirt embellished by a giant nautical motif. The entire Ferre collection, presented in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> Tuesday, was an ode to the sea, with navy blue and white stripes the dominant pattern and anchors, compasses and life preservers printed everywhere. At the height of the miniskirt mania last year, <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON>, known for his staid fashion, shocked the fashion crowd with the shortest, tightest look on the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> runway. In keeping with the current search for lost innocence, his spring-summer collection brings hemlines right down to the ankle and softens the silhouette with wide tops and loose-fitting pants. Extra feminine touches were offered by the high sailor suit waistline on skirts and pants, and enticing see-through, star-sequined T-shirts. Evening at <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> was all stars and stripes in long shimmery evening gowns, the tightest seen thus far on this week's Italian ready-to-wear runway. On Wednesday, the fourth day of the five day showings, <PERSON> Basile </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ferragamo </PERSON> continued the trend toward calmer, more feminine styles. <PERSON> Luciano </PERSON> <PERSON> Soprani </PERSON>, for <PERSON> Basile </PERSON>, picked dainty floral prints for his super-soft long skirts worn under a neat tight waisted blazer or a belted Safari jacket. Evening wear turned the fashion page back to the heyday of the debutante ball. Dressed in their empire-waisted full-skirted strapless evening gowns, they looked as innocent as a busload of college freshmenn at their first mixer. Even when the rest of <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> was vying for the shortest look, <PERSON> Ferragamo </PERSON> persevered in its classic tailored style, with a discreet knee-skimming hemline. It took the sedate Florentine tailors little effort to lengthen this look to mid-calf in slim unfussy skirts worn under a simple short-sleeved linen blazer. The classic look continued in the Chanel-inspired little black day suits with gold buttons worn with a Ferragamo logo T-shirt. <PERSON> Ferragamo </PERSON>, famous for its shoes, capitalized on its own classics by dotting the collection with little golden shoes as lapel pins and charms on a bracelet.
