<HEAD>Foreign Investment Disclosure Bill Clears House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign investors with a `` significant interest'' in American business or property would have to disclose their holdings to the government under legislation approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. `` Give us the opportunity to have a basic inventory of ownership of the American economy,'' Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, the sponsor, said as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved the measure 250-170 on Wednesday. The measure now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where its chances for approval are dim. Those owning more than 5 percent of a business or property valued at more than $ 5 million or that has more than $ 10 million in annual gross sales would have to report their identity and holdings to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The measure also would apply to investors holding more than 5 percent of a combination of two or more businesses or properties valued at more than $ 20 million or with annual gross sales of more than $ 40 million. Foreigners with `` controlling interests'' in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses and properties would be required to submit more extensive reports, including balance sheets and the identities of officers and directors. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would establish a registry of foreign interests owning <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> property. Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, D-Tenn., described the measure as `` election-year xenophobia'' designed to capitalize on fear of foreigners among voters Supporters retorted that foreign takeover of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets should not occur in secret. `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people have the right to know who holds the mortgage on <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' Rep. <PERSON> Marcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaptur </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, declared. The bill originally was included in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s version of a wide-ranging trade measure signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Aug. 23. But sponsors, seeking to build support for the trade bill, dropped the foreign ownership provision before it went to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The foreign ownership disclosure bill is now moving forward as separate legislation. The measure's prospects are dim in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where it would be vulnerable to a time-consuming filibuster with only days remaining until lawmakers adjourn to campaign full time. Critics say the bill would bare business secrets that ought to be private, thus scaring off foreigners whose investment helps to finance the budget deficit and fuels the economy, creating jobs for Americans. `` The issue is confidentiality,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lent </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION> `` This bill does n't have adequate safeguards.'' Data on foreign ownership of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> property already is collected by 17 federal agencies. But the information is often kept secret, even from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and in any case the names of the actual owners rarely appear. Complaints persist that even those reports are often incomplete, inaccurate and largely meaningless and that hundreds of billions of dollars in new investment have simply fallen through the cracks in recent years. Opponents also blasted the bill as discriminatory toward foreign investors because Americans would not have to provide the same information.
</TEXT>
