<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-06 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Consumers Likely To Feel Effects Of Wheat Price Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new Agriculture Department analysis of this summer's drought-induced rise in wheat prices says consumers might feel some effect at grocery stores at least through 1989. `` Past movements suggest that the drought's influence on farm prices of wheat will be felt for about a year at the industrial -LRB- wholesale -RRB- level and for a year and a half or more by consumers,'' the report said. The study was done by <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Babula </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bessler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; <ORGANIZATION> M </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and reported in the current issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine <PERSON> Babula </PERSON> said Wednesday in a telephone interview that he and <PERSON> Bessler </PERSON> are not forcasting how food prices will behave in the coming months. Prices of various items could decline but still leave some impact from the 1988 drought. `` We're not predicting anything,'' <PERSON> Babula </PERSON> said. `` We're showing how things have moved in the past ... and some of the things that we might expect to see happen in the future.'' A statistical computer model was used to show how prices of wheat at the farm, wholesale prices and retail prices have moved together in the past. The model was then `` shocked'' with an increase in the farm price of wheat to simulate the 7.7 percent average monthly boost during May, June and July, when the effects of the drought were first reflected in the market. `` When the farm price shock occurs, processor -LRB- wholesale -RRB- prices for wheat rise immediately, peaking a month after the rise in the farm price,'' the report said. `` At their highest, processor prices increase less than half of the 7.7 percent increase in the farm price. Processor price increases are felt for about a year, but the impulse generally declines in strength through time.'' On the other hand, the 7.7 percent average increase in the farm price of wheat `` generates gradual, not immediate, increases in consumer prices of wheat-related goods,'' the report said. Delivery, sale and consumption of flour, bread, cake mixes, pasta and other wheat-related foods occur throughout the year and are not as closely tied to the wheat crop cycle as processing, which includes the flour milling and baking industries. `` So, the consumer price effects last more than a year,'' the report said. `` Consumer price rises peak at seven months, but prices stay relatively high until 17 to 20 months after the initiating farm price shock. The increase in consumer prices is smaller but more enduring than the jump in processor prices.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some promising new biological weapons are being used in the war against marauding grasshoppers, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. In one development, two commercial firms _ <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> BioControl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON> Bio Tech of <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. _ have adapted <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> technology for producing and storing a parasite, Nosema lucustae. Department studies show the parasite kills 50 percent to 60 percent of grasshoppers in three to four weeks. The basic tests and development were done by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> at the agency's <ORGANIZATION> Rangeland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON> by J.E <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> and colleagues. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said the parasite is available to homeowners and ranchers through regional agents and on contract to government agencies, which use it on a large scale in the West. <ORGANIZATION> Grasshoppers </ORGANIZATION> cause an estimated $ 400 million in damage to grass and crops each year, he said. Spores of the parasite are put on wheat bran flakes to form a bait. After the insects eat the bait, the organism `` attacks the pest's fat cells and depletes its energy stores,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said in a report issued here on Wednesday. The parasite remains in the grasshopper population because sick females pass it on to offspring, and survivors eat dead relatives, he said. Meanwhile, another development involves an agreement with <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> <PERSON> Biotechnical </PERSON> to field test another natural killer, grasshopper entomopoxvirus, the agency said. In laboratory tests, the virus kills 20 percent to 30 percent of the grasshoppers right away and stunts the growth of an additional 20 percent to 30 percent. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Streett </PERSON>, an entomoligist at the agency's <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON> laboratory, said <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> BioControl </ORGANIZATION> plans to produce the virus and mix it with the parasite for tests on 1,000 acres in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Streett </PERSON> said that in combination the two ingredients may work more rapidly to kill the grasshoppers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ice cream production in August was estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> at 87.7 million gallons, up 4 percent from a year earlier. That did n't count 39.4 million gallons of ice milk, a 20 percent increase from August 1987, or 5.21 million gallons of sherbet, up 13 percent. August production figures issued on Wednesday also showed butter output at 74.2 million pounds, up 12 percent from a year earlier. Production of American-type cheese, at 214 million pounds, was up 4 percent. Production of non-fat dry milk was reported at 66.6 million pounds, down 17 percent from August 1987.
</TEXT>
