<HEAD>Pinochet One Of Few Authoritarian Leaders Remaining In Latin
America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> is one of the few authoritarian leaders left in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, where elected civilian government has returned to most countries. The nearest geographically is Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, who has ruled <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> since seizing power in 1954. President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has governed <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> since leading a successful revolution in 1959 and installing a communist regime. In <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> qualifies as an authoritarian leader but is not technically the chief of state. Elected civilian governments have replaced military regimes in the last few years in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>. Military governments ruled <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> for two decades until 1985. Five generals took turns as president, chosen by their peers and sharing power with them. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s armed forces ousted civilian President <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> in March 1976 and retained power until 1983, leaving in disgrace after defeat in the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> war with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Governing was an act of the military institution in both countries, but the regimes of <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, 72, and <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, 75, are personal. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> declared a few years ago: `` Not a single leaf moves in this country unless I move it,'' and <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> probably could say the same.
</TEXT>
