<FIRST>r i PM-PinochetProfile     10-06 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pinochet Profile,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet: Combative With An Anti-Communist Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has been tireless in what he sees as a mission from God to reconstruct a new, communist-proof society. Shrewd and combative, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> successfully resisted the regional trend toward elected civilian rule that prevailed in many Latin American countries in the 1980s. His right-wing authoritarian regime, he says, is a bulwark against Marxism. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> took power in 1973 in a coup that toppled the elected government of Marxist President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>. The takeover won wide support because it occurred at a time of social unrest and economic chaos. Few, however, could have predicted <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> would remain in power this long. But <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> immediately banned all political activity and purged the nation of tens of thousands of leftists. Most were expelled, although hundreds were imprisoned and scores were tortured and executed, according to human rights groups. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> also outmaneuvered the commanders of the navy, air force and national police, who were initially supposed to alternate with him as the country's ruler. Using his muscle as army commander, the most powerful of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s military branches, he emerged as the sole leader. Born Nov. 25, 1915, in the port city of <LOCATION> Valparaiso </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was one of three children of a customs official. Ignoring parental pleas to study medicne, he entered the military academy, after twice being rejected as too young and physically weak. In the army he filled out to 185 pounds and earned a university degree. Now, he boasts a boxer's physique and is said to lifts weight daily. He is reported to drink little. According to a 1980 autobiography, he noted an international Marxist threat while commanding a camp for Communist prisoners in 1948 and lectured on the dangers of communism while teaching at the national war college. However, when <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> became president <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remained outwardly loyal and was named army commander a month before the coup. Some participants in the takeover said he joined the conspiracy opportunistically at the last minute. The political repression that followed the coup earned <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> an image as a brutish dictator. Repression included the assasination of critics in exile, including <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Letelier </PERSON>, killed in a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> car bombing in 1976. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has denounced foreign criticism as interferring in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s internal affairs. He announced plans to reshape Chilean society and construct safeguards against communism. A Constitution approved in a 1980 referendum bans all ideologies based on class struggle. It also included a phased return to democracy and called for the presidential plebiscite that occurred Wednesday. He launched a free-market economic program that, coupled with heavy foreign borrowing and an overvalued currency, produced a financial near-collapse in the early 1980s. Massive anti-government protests threatened to topple his government. But he moderated his policies, winning even the begrudged praise of his opponents with five years of steady economic growth and stability. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> preaches patriotism, family values and hard work. His stern demeanor appeals to many common Chileans, but his behavior bothers most educated citizens. He often appears in public with his wife, <PERSON> Lucia </PERSON>. They have three daughters and two sons. In recent years, especially since a September 1986 assasination attempt by leftist guerrillas, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has come to cite God. In 1987 he declared, `` God put me on the top.'' Now obsessed with personal security, his motorcade routinely includes four cars of heavily armed bodyguards, a van carry an army commando unit, an ambulance and an army helicopter gunship.
</TEXT>
