<HEAD>Congress Putting Final Touches To Radon Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is putting the finishing touches on a campaign to reduce indoor exposure to radon, the naturally occurring gas that health officials say is second only to smoking as a cause of lung cancer deaths. Pending in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is House-passed legislation that would require inspections of public schools for dangerous levels of radon and set a long-term national goal of having indoor air as free of the gas as the air outdoors. Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, said he expects the bill to easily clear the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in the closing days of the 1988 session and go to the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, where it already has been endorsed by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. The broadly supported legislation, which won voice-vote approval in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday, is moving toward the statute books in the wake of a recent warning by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The agencies advised people to have their residences tested for radon, an odorless, colorless gas produced by the decay of uranium deposits found in the ground in many parts of the nation. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> and USPHS estimated that nationally one of every 10 houses could have dangerous levels of radon. They said they believe such levels are present in about 25 percent of the homes in 17 states where radon deposits are prevalent. Authorities have estimated that indoor concentrations of radon are responsible for as many as 20,000 lung cancer deaths annually. The House-passed bill would require <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to conduct a national survey of school buildings and advise local education agencies about ways of reducing high concentrations of radon. It would authorize $ 30 million over the next three years for a matching grant program to help states set up their own radon control programs. Less than half the states now have such programs. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> would be required to set up training programs to teach state and local officials proper techniques for radon monitoring, assessment and mitigation. It also would have to set standards for certifying radon measuring devices and rating the effectiveness of radon-control contractors. Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, the bill's floor manager in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said these provisions are needed to protect homeowners from unscrupulous contractors and profiteers. `` New radon testing and mitigation companies spring up overnight, and unfortunately not all of them are qualified or scrupulous,'' he said. `` Contractors have charged as much as $ 4,000 when they could have charged $ 1,000 and still profited nicely,'' <PERSON> Luken </PERSON> said. `` Even worse, salespeople have tried to palm off fly paper and vacuum cleaners as testing and mitigation devices.'' The bill also would create a process under which state and local building codes would eventually be revised to require the use of construction techniques that would minimize the entry of radon into structures. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has set 4 picocuries of radon per liter of air as the level at which homeowners should take steps to make their houses more resistant to radon seepage from the ground. House sponsors of the bill say it is uncertain whether this level is fully protective of human health during long-term exposure to indoor radon. They said this is why they want to set a national goal of minimizing exposure to radon.
</TEXT>
