<FIRST>r i PM-Europe-AcidRain     10-06 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe-Acid Rain,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Research Reveals Widespread Pollution in European Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Acid rain has polluted more than half of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s lakes and rivers, and the contamination has spread much farther than earlier believed, an international report said. The report, which was released Wednesday, said nearly all small bodies of water in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are so badly contaminated that they can no longer be used for drinking water. It also said the actual damage could be much worse because the research was based mainly on information provided by the countries involved. `` In some cases, it is too late to do anything,'' said <PERSON> Kaarle </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenttamies </PERSON>, head of the Finnish <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> team which conducted the survey for the U.N.-sponsored Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution. `` In other countries, particularly the peripheral regions such as <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION> and southernmost <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, there is still hope,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` But many small lakes and rivers, especially in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, are dead, and only a 100 percent drop in sulfur emissions can save them,'' he said. He also said dumping heavy doses of lime could also help reduce acidity. The year-long research project showed nearly all smaller bodies of water in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> can no longer be used as sources of drinking water, <PERSON> Kenttamies </PERSON> said. Acid rain carries a high concentration of acids produced by sulfur dioxide, nitrogen oxide and other chemicals emitted during the burning of fossil fuels. The U.N.-sponsored conference, which drew participants from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and nine west European nations, urged the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to adopt stricter measures to fight pollution caused by nitrogen and sulfur emissions. The commission's member countries have decided to start a joint international pollution monitoring project in 1989 to study environmental changes caused by acid rain. `` Despite certain opposition to such research, particularly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, we can can safely say that acidification is one of the worst pollution problems of the 1980s,'' <PERSON> Kenttamies </PERSON> said. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has been criticized by environmentalists for failing to do more to solve the problem of acid rain during his two terms in office. In August, however, he gave the go-ahead for continuing negotiations toward <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participation in an international treaty to freeze emissions of a precursor to acid rain. <PERSON> Kenttamies </PERSON> rejected as `` nonsense'' the argument that no conclusive evidence exists that fossil fuel-fired power stations contribute heavily to acid rain. `` Whatever people say, I've seen enough reports and been to enough conventions like the one here today to know that we have such conclusive evidence,'' he said. The high cost of fighting acid rain is a problem for countries which rely heavily on fossil fuels. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, both heavy coal users, are the only European nations which refused to join in a project to reduce sulfur emissions by 30 percent of 1980 levels by 1993. Acid rain in <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, mostly from industrial centers in eastern and western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, also has contaminated lakes and forests. Finns were recently shocked to learn of heavy pollution in what had been considered virgin <LOCATION> Lapland </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> caused by huge Soviet copper and nickel works in the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>.
