<FIRST>r w PM-SocialSecurityCOLAs     10-06 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Security COLAs,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House: No `Elderly' Index Needed To Figure Social Security
COLAs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration sees no need to change the formula for calculating cost-of-living increases for Social Security and other entitlements despite claims that millions of beneficiaries are being shortchanged. White House Budget Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> on Wednesday said it `` would make no difference'' in what the government spends on those increases if one <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> consumer price index were subsituted for another in figuring the increases. But in a written statement to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said, `` I do not believe any changes are needed at the present time.'' The panel's chairman, Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON>, D-Mont., has introduced two bills that would immediately substitute one inflation survey for the other in calculating benefit increases and spend $ 1.5 million to develop a new survey devoted only to price changes experienced by the elderly With figures due out in two weeks on how big an increase 38 million Social Security recipients can expect in their checks next year, the committee held hearings on <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON>'s proposals Wednesday. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> cited a <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study showing that families headed by people 65 or over have experienced `` the largest real income gains of any age group between 1970 and 1986.'' `` Social Security beneficiaries have in fact been well protected from inflation over the last decade and a half under the exisiting cost-of-living provisions,'' he said. `` Poverty rates among the elderly have been cut in half over this period.'' Since 1978, the government has used annualized third-quarter changes in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer price index for urban wage earners and clerical workers -LRB- CPI-W -RRB- to calculate the annual benefit increases. Last year, for example, annualized inflation as measured by that index for that quarter was 4.2 percent, yielding Social Security recipients an average $ 21 a month increase in their benefit checks. <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON> and advocacy groups for the elderly want the government to switch to a more widely used price index for urban households -LRB- CPI-U -RRB- immediately, while developing an entirely new CPI-E for the elderly for eventual use in calculating the benefit changes. At Wednesday's hearing, <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON> said the CPI-W understates the increases that the elderly actually are experiencing because it does not take into account the higher percentages of their income spent on medical care and housing. Annual differences in the CPI-U and CPI-W indexes have ranged from 0.1 percent to 0.5 percent over the past five years. But cumulated inflation as measured by the wage earners survey totaled 16.5 percent over the five years compared with 18.2 percent as measured by the more widely accepted urban household survey. `` This means that millions of retirees who depend on benefits or pensions from these programs may not be getting a square deal,'' <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON> said. `` If all the costs of the elderly were figured in, -LRB- annual -RRB- COLAs would be higher as much as $ 5 a month. For some people $ 5 is n't very much money, but for many elderly $ 5 is a lot of money.'' At <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON>'s instigation, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year constructed an experimental index measuring only the inflation experienced by consumers age 62 and over. Reflecting that the elderly spend nearly 9 percent of their income on medical costs compared with roughly 5 percent spent by urban households in general, it showed inflation over the past five years totaling 19.5 percent for those 62 and over. Had the experimental index been in use, the average Social Security retiree would have received a total of $ 528 in additional benefits over the past five years, said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Yarrington </PERSON>, a policy analyst for an advocacy group, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to Preserve Social Security and <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. However, Labor Statistics Commissioner <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Norwood </PERSON> said the experimental survey had larger sampling errors than the official measures.
</TEXT>
