<FIRST>r w PM-MoneyLaundering     10-06 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Laundering,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kerry, McConnell Vow To Add Money Laundering Provision To Drug
Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> narcotics panel says foreign banks must be forced to keep records of large cash transactions to help block laundering of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug profits. `` Cash, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars, are the stock and trade of narcotics traffickers and currently there is a gigantic loophole,'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., said Wednesday <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Relations subcommittee on narcotics and terrorism, said an estimated $ 30 billion to $ 100 billion in drug-tied <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cash is laundered each year. He and <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, R-Ky., the panel's ranking Republican, said that when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> begins debate on sweeping drug legislation they would push an amendment designed to create a paper trail for prosecutors Debate on the drug legislation is expected to start before the end of next week, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourns for campaigning. Major drug traffickers now take <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug profits by plane or boat to nations in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and deposit huge chunks of cash in banks there, often under phony corporation names, <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said. The dealers then have the banks wire the money to the institutions' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> branches. In that way, drug traffickers can launder their illegal profits and avoid federal regulations that require banks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to maintain strict records of cash transactions of $ 10,000 or more. The <ORGANIZATION> Kerry-McConnell </ORGANIZATION> proposal would extend that requirement to foreign banks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> branches as well as to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> banks with overseas offices. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said he expected strong opposition from large banks. `` This bill will destabilize drug dealers' criminal networks by denying them free access to the American banking system,'' <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> said. `` It will give law enforcement officials the tools necessary to trace and seize drug assets and prosecute those criminals right out of business.'' The Kerry-McConnell amendment would require the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to negotiate within two years agreements with nations that have been identified as key money-laundering centers. Under the legislation, all offshore banks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ties would be required to maintain records of cash transactions of $ 10,000 or more, obtain from those depositors a waiver of privacy rights if the records are needed in a drug-related investigation, and obtain from depositors personal identification and documents stating the source of the money. `` With enactment of this amendment, international drug dealers will have to find a black market dry cleaner for their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars because all the legitimate laundromats will be closed to them,'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> told a news conference.
</TEXT>
