<HEAD>Proposal To Combat `Greenhouse Effect' Focuses On Energy
Efficiency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new House bill designed to combat the `` greenhouse effect,'' or global warming trend, would require a wide range of energy-saving measures, including a higher `` gas guzzler'' tax and rebates for buyers of fuel-efficient autos. Republican and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers said Wednesday in introducing the legislation that they did not expect action on the bill before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourns next week. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has said more study is needed before taking action to curb the greenhouse effect. Rep. <PERSON> Claudine </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION>, chief architect of the new proposal, said available options for reducing greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide can vary in cost by ten-fold or more. `` This makes it imperative that the strategy the federal government undertakes in formulating global warming prevention policies avoids imposing needless and wasteful expenditures ...,'' she said. The global warming trend, which some scientists say already has begun, could raise the average temperature of the earth by 3 degrees to 8 degrees in the middle of the next century. The warming comes about because gases arising from human activity build up in the atmosphere, trapping radiant heat that normally would escape to space. The most important gas, carbon dioxide, comes from the burning of fossil fuels such as oil and coal. Also on Wednesday, a report from the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a companion organization to the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, called for a ` first priority'' on energy efficiency by the next administration. The report said political leaders must be willing to raise the consumer cost of using fuels that produce carbon dioxide. A prominent example would be gasoline. Ms. <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>'s measure calls for substantial increases in funds for research and development, modification of federal buildings to create 40 percent energy savings by the end of the century, tough efficiency standards for electric lights and major increases in auto fuel efficiency along with a higher `` gas-guzzler'' tax and rebates for buyers of efficient models.
</TEXT>
