inistration has paid too little attention to the rest of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. Said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>: `` There's no doubt, in a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration that the aid would be cut off to the democratic resistance in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and that is unfortunate.'' He said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> seemed to think it was all right for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` to put in billions of dollars to prop up the communist <PERSON> Sandinistas </PERSON>, but somehow it's wrong for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to give a few dollars to the democratic resistance.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he still supported the Monroe Doctrine, set forth in 1823 by President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would oppose any attempt by European powers to interfere in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>. And he said 85 percent Americans supported the 1983 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, but that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had criticized it. `` We turned a communist country into a non-communist country,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` The governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> is simply out of step with mainstream <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> noted that both he and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> speak Spanish and said they wanted to launch a new alliance for progress for <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, `` a country with 85 million people sharing a 2,000-mile border with us, with half of those people under the age of 15, a country that has had its standard of living cut 50 percent in the last six years.'' `` We ought to be concerned about that and we ought to be involved,'' he said. `` Bring in the Europeans _ the Spanish, who have a real affinity for that area. Bring in the Japanese, who have a great capital surplus now and looking for places to invest it.'' Such investment could foster peace, raise the standard of living and provide the stability needed for democracy to prosper, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said.
