<HEAD>Rowdy Crowd, Testy Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crowd was rowdy. Throughout the vice presidential debate, the candidates were greeted with derisive laughter and raucous cheers from alternating sides of an auditorium calculatedly divided evenly between Republicans and Democrats, down to the very last partisan. Throughout it all <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> doggedly stuck to their podiums, exchanging occasional glares. `` It sure was n't hermetically sealed,'' laughed <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Touhy </PERSON>, who produced the debate program for a bipartisan commission. `` For a while, I was afraid they were going to rush the stage.'' Both candidates and workers had spent the week in intense preparation over the smallest details, and the training was apparent from the time the two candidates strode purposefully on stage in matching dark suits and similar striped ties. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s sole concession to informality was a foot propped casually on his podium, while <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> stubbornly gripped a pen in his right hand, occasionally stabbing the air to underscore a point. The debate started slowly, but tension between the candidates grew, capped when <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> glared at <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and said: `` Senator, you are no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' The two candidates shook hands at the beginning and end, but there was little warmth in between, and the crowd paid scant attention to repeated pleas from moderator <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON>, of the `` MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour'' television program, to react less noisily. The candidates generally stared stonily into space during the demonstrations, picking up where they left off after it subsided. `` I'm wondering if the rowdiness of the crowd does n't dictate that future debates will be held in television studios rather than a public auditorium,'' <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> said later. `` It was a pretty rowdy crowd.'' The candidates occasionally had some tensions with their questioners also. Pressed repeatedly to give his qualifications for president, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> at one point snapped `` I think this is the fourth time I've had this question. No, he was told, just the third. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, pressed to explain a fund-raising tactic, stiffened a bit before saying `` I do n't find it embarrassing at all.'' Organizers made no apologies for the stiffness of the arrangements, telling reporters it was their job to produce good television. And that's precisely what came out _ a television program staged as artfully as a sitcom. `` This is a television program, and we've got some of the best production people in the world doing it,'' <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> said. `` You direct a television program so people watching at home have a good idea what's happening.'' The League of Women Voters originally was to sponsor the second presidential debate, next week in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, but pulled out charging the candidates exercised too much control over the format and turned the event into a `` charade.'' That sort of criticism, insisted <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON>, was `` a lot of nonsense.'' `` I'm delighted that it went well,'' <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> said. `` There was real substance. This was not a battle of the network sound bites.'' The show will go on. Saws and hammers came out within minutes of the debate's close, dismantling a stage that had been shipped to <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, and the first debate between <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Next stop is <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and the final presidential debate.
