<HEAD>Weather Postpones Medfly Spraying After Beverly Hills Takes Cover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with spraying postponed;
picks up 4th graf, `The target ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> residents threw tarpaulins over their Porsches and Ferraris and others stayed indoors Wednesday as the state prepared a sticky aerial bombardment of <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> fruit fly pesticide. But low clouds late Wednesday grounded three helicopters that were set to spray Malathion over a 35-square-mile swath of homes and businesses west of downtown, including sections of <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, to stop a burgeoning infestation of the crop-destroying pest. The spraying was rescheduled for Thursday night, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, chief deputy to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s agricultural commissioner. The target area is densely packed with homes and businesses. Forty Medflies have been found in yards since Sept. 26, indicating a serious infestation that, if allowed to spread, could threaten crops worth $ 8 billion a year statewide, authorities said. While the most exclusive residential sections of <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, including shaded streets dotted with movie stars' mansions, were not included in the spraying area, many of the community's expensive shops and opulent apartment buildings fell into the target zone, along with other sections of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and other municipalities with homes ranging from modest bungalows to estates The nearest commercial crops are dozens of miles away from the spray area, but the pest can spread rapidly. Medflies lay their eggs under the skin of a wide variety of fruits and vegetables, hatching maggots that destroy the crop. The last serious infestation, in 1980 and 1981, cost <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> farmers an estimated $ 100 million. `` We need to get this done as quickly as possible,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said of the spraying. State experts say the spraying could cause inconvenience, but no health hazard, as the Malathion in the small concentrations used is harmless to warm-blooded animals. However, the pesticide is mixed with a sweet, sticky corn syrup bait that can damage car paint. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON>, who runs Scandinavian Auto Body, scrambled to find tarpaulins or garage space for a fleet of <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Romeos </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. `` You're looking at about $ 7,500 in refinishing that would have to be done,'' <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON> said. Agricultural Commissioner <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Spaugy </PERSON> said the fight to save the state's farm industry knows no economic boundaries. `` We're encouraging people to cover up their Rolls Royces just like they would cover up their Pintos,'' he said Among the cities and the sections of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in the area are <LOCATION> Culver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Palms, <LOCATION> Baldwin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> started passing out flyers notifying residents of the spraying Monday, and there have been news reports all week, but some objected they had n't been warned in time. West Hollywood Mayor <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>, in a letter to state agriculture officials, complained the city had n't been given enough time to warn its residents or assess possible health hazards. Responded Edwards: `` They should be mad at the people who caused this -LRB- infestation -RRB-, and that's the people who brought the -LRB- contaminated -RRB- fruit in. We're trying to protect the state's biggest industry, and that's agriculture If we do n't do this, farmers are going to have to use a lot more pesticide and fruit is going to cost more.'' The Medfly is native to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and other tropical areas. Most <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> infestations are believed to start with flies unwittingly brought home by tourists in illegally transported fruit, or in fruit mailed from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The anti-Medfly strategy is two-fold. First, the population is knocked down with the Malathion bait, which remains active about a week. Then, millions of specially bred sterile flies are released so the surviving wild flies mate harmlessly.
