<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Military President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> lost a referendum that would have allowed him to stay in power until 1997, government and opposition returns showed Thursday. The defeat sets the stage for open elections next year. In a speech broadcast nationwide on television and radio, Interior Minister <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, formally conceded <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s defeat at 2:40 a.m. -LRB- 1:40 a.m. EDT -RRB- `` We abide by the results, which the country already knows,'' <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> said. Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Commander General <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON>, a member of the law-making military junta, said: `` It seem to me that the ` no' -LRB- vote -RRB- has won.'' `` We are calm. We are going to analyze the situation,'' <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON> added as he entered the downtown government palace at 1 a.m. for an emergency meeting with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the four-man junta and the 15-member Cabinet. Shortly after <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON>'s statement, the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> at 2:10 a.m. announced for the first time substantial voting returns that showed the vote against <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s continued rule prevailing. It earlier had said <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was winning. With 15,969 of the country's 22,248 voting tables reporting, the ministry counted 2,754,805 votes, or 53.3 percent, against <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, and 2,290,972 votes, or 44.3 percent, supporting the president. There were also 53,292 blank votes and 68,108 votes voided for being wrongly marked. An earlier opposition tally gave the `` no'' vote an even wider margin with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> losing, 57.8 percent to 39.9 percent. <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and spokesman for the coalition, declared, `` It's clear that the majority of Chileans have voted no.'' On Wednesday in balloting that was peaceful and heavily attended, Chileans voted on a proposal by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and other military commanders that he remain president until 1997. The right-wing, 72-year-old army chief seized power in a bloody coup in 1973 that ousted the 3-year-old elected government of President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist who died during the takeover. If he had won, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> would have assumed a new 8-year term in March. By losing, an open presidential election is to be held late next year and the winner would assume power in March 1990, with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining in power until then. Earlier, military patrols in armored personnel carriers and trucks with mounted machine guns were seen circulating in working-class neighborhoods and slums _ where anti-Pinochet sentiment traditionally runs high _ that ring the capital. A few hundred people danced in the streets of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> slum in southern <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, waving banners and celebrating an anticipated `` no'' victory. `` We all voted no, because we are repressed,'' said one participant, 50-year-old construction worker <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrido </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Zincke </PERSON>, military commander for the <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> area, reported scattered incidents after the voting, which he said were being controlled by police. He said anti-government demonstrators erected barricades in the streets of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardo </LOCATION>, south of the capital, and <LOCATION> Puente </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, to the southeast. He said six people were arrested for carrying arms and a public bus was burned and its driver beaten. <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>'s streets were mainly empty as most Chileans heeded opposition calls to stay at home. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said earlier in an interview broadcast by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperativa </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, `` So far everything is calm, but I've got some information that leaves me thinking. There are some people who have seen individuals wearing ski-masks.'' He gave no details. Leftist urban guerrillas commonly employ ski masks, but both of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s guerrilla groups have publicly announced a truce until after the voting day. A huge turnout among the 7.4 million registered voters slowed balloting at many polling places and could delay definitive tallies, authorities said. Voting tables started closing at 5 p.m. and the counting began. Foreign observers said the plebiscite appeared to be open and honestly conducted. Former President <PERSON> Oswaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, an observer, said: `` What I have seen is Chileans being able to cast their votes freely and in private.'' Official returns from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> are not expected until Friday. Voting is mandatory and those who do n't vote can be fined up to 22,000 pesos, or about $ 80. In <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, the capital city where more than one-third of the nation's 12 million people live, some voters showed up an hour before polls began opening at 8 a.m. Lines more than a mile long had formed by midmorning, under bright sunlight in the Southern Hemisphere spring. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, smiling and wearing a beige civilian suit, voted at a downtown <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> station.
