<HEAD>Public Booze Ban Planned To Curb Rowdy Youths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVENTRY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government says it will ban public drinking in eight English cities next year in an experimental crackdown on so-called `` lager louts'' _ rowdy youths who get drunk on American-style beer. Home Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said the bans would take effect early next year in <LOCATION> Coventry </LOCATION>, Bath, <LOCATION> Farnborough </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chester </PERSON>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Austell </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Scarborough </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Aldershot </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Newquay </LOCATION>. `` The government does not want to restrict personal freedom,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> told a legal conference Wednesday. `` But it is not clever, masculine or attractive to drink yourself into a state where you break windows or hit or stab a policemen.'' The two-year experimental program calls for local governments to work with the Home Office to enact by-laws empowering the courts to levy $ 170 fines against people who drink alcohol outdoors. The measure follows a wave of summer violence in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s suburbs and rural towns by young men, most of them between the ages of 18 and 26, who gather on weekends and drink on the streets or in local pubs They have been blamed for brawls, vandalism and attacks on unarmed police called to disperse the drunken, rowdy crowds. Police estimate dozens of officers have been injured in confrontations nationwide with the so-called `` lager louts.'' Lager is a pale, American-style beer favored by the young as opposed to the dark, traditional `` bitter'' English beer. Traditionally, Britons have been allowed to consume alcohol in parks or on the streets, particularly during the afternoon when pubs are closed. But the 73-year-old pub-closing law was repealed Aug. 22, giving people who want a pint of beer in the afternoon the option to drink indoors. <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said Wednesday he had misgivings about making drinking on the streets a criminal offense. `` But I concluded that the ... distress caused to ordinary citizens by groups of mainly young people becoming drunk and behaving badly was such that it was worth trying a by-law,'' he said. In a meeting today with the Chief Police Officers Association in the northern city of <LOCATION> Preston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> was to be asked to endorse another experimental program: installing video cameras in downtown areas to keep on eye on drunken youths.
</TEXT>
