<HEAD>Many Voted Early To Avoid Long Lines And Possible Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs and edits to reflect referendum result;
picks up 9th graf, `About 7.4 ...'
^With PM-Chile, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chileans grew frustrated with long lines that snaked outside polling stations, but many believed the national referendum on whether Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> should continue as president would be fair and accurate. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> conceded early today that <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> had lost the referendum. Voters had been asked to decide whether <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who seized power in a 1973 military coup, should continue to rule this South American nation until 1997. Open elections for a new president are to be held next year. During Wednesday's balloting, many Chileans seemed confident that their vote would count. `` I'll respect the results even if <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> wins,'' said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Casanova </PERSON>, a 63-year-old retired farmer, standing outside a polling station in a working-class northern suburb. `` I think <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> will respect the results even if he loses.'' `` Anyone who wants to can vote ` no.' That does n't happen in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and a lot of other countries,'' said <PERSON> Geronima </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON>, 54, who was waiting her turn in the affluent <LOCATION> Providencia </LOCATION> neighborhood of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. `` We have a beautiful democracy, with order and discipline.'' About 7.4 million people were registered to vote. Voting is mandatory, and turnout was heavy across this narrow country wedged between the snow-capped <LOCATION> Andes </LOCATION> mountains and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. Anyone who did not vote soon after polls opened at 8 a.m. risked a long wait under a glaring spring sun. Men removed their sport coats and sweaters, and women, standing in separate lines, fanned themselves or held kerchiefs over their heads. Government television said two elderly voters, in the cities of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Serena </LOCATION> and Coyhaique, suffered heart attacks and died just before or after voting. But few people grumbled, and even fewer went home without voting. `` I took three buses to get here,'' said <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON>, at a southern <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> polling place. Housewife <PERSON> Sonia </PERSON> <PERSON> Azoca </PERSON> in the northern neighborhood of <PERSON> Conchali </PERSON> said: `` I've been here half an hour. I'll probably be here an hour more. However long it takes, I'll be here.'' National police in white suspenders, holsters and carrying batons were posted at each of the 1,000 polling stations nationwide. Otherwise, the military was barely visible in the capital's streets, sidewalks and parks, which were practically deserted. After voting, most people took the advice of the government, the opposition and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. They went home. Not one of more than a dozen voters interviewed doubted the vote count would be fast and accurate. `` Fraud is impossible,'' said <PERSON> Fabiola </PERSON> <PERSON> Escuer </PERSON>, 24. `` Both sides are counting the vote and there are observers from many countries.'' Election laws provide for pollwatchers from both pro-government and opposition parties. An estimated 500 foreign observers were on hand in the capital and provincial cities.
