<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign observers who watched as Chileans decided whether Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> should remain as president said the balloting appeared fair but frequently disorganized. `` What I have seen is Chileans being able to cast their votes freely and in private ...,'' said <PERSON> Oswaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON>, former president of <LOCATION> Ecuado </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said early today that a majority voted against <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining as president until 1997. New elections are to be held next year. Opposition groups fearful of fraud by the government had urged foreign dignitaries to monitor the vote. More than 500 politicians, diplomats and a few celebrities _ including Nicaraguan actress <PERSON> Bianca </PERSON> <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> _ chose to do so. `` Some polling stations were badly organized. Some opened late and consequently will have to remain open longer this evening, but in general ... it has gone rather well,'' said <PERSON> Johanna </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON> <PERSON> Weggen </PERSON>, a European Parliament delegate from the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. Former presidents <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Misael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>, former governor of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, led a 60-member delegation of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. They visited polling stations in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> and 10 other cities but said they would not comment formally until a ne