<HEAD>CAMPAIGN FINANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Asked if he was embarrassed at being the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s biggest recipient of contributions from political action committees, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said he plays by the laws as they are, just like when `` you're paying taxes or you're playing a football game.'' But <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> acknowledged his $ 10,000-a-plate `` breakfast club'' for lobbyists was `` a real doozie'' of a mistake which he quickly ended. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` He disbanded the club, but he's still got the money,'' since most of the lobbyists forked over donations anyway to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman's campaign. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> had pocketed more than a quarter-million dollars in speech honoraria from special interest groups.
