<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen today, while share prices fell sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 133.30 yen, down 0.18 yen from Wednesday's close of 133.48 yen Opening at 133.37 yen, the currency moved in a range of 133.30-133 .53 yen The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 95.53-point loser the previous day, lost another 233.15 points, or 0.85 percent, to close at 27,172.34 points. `` Share prices fell mainly because the market will have a three-day holiday this weekend, in addition to investors' cautiousness before the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment figures,'' said <PERSON> Manji </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> monthly unemployment rate for September is due to be released Friday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The market's fall in recent sessions has been contradicting almost ideal economic factors surrounding the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market, <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> said, suggesting that the condition of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s ailing emperor has been a market-affecting factor. In foreign exchange, trading was quiet before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment report, said <PERSON> Mitsuhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON> with the <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` The dollar-yen rate was moving very little as investors traded the currencies only for speculative reasons and position adjustment,'' he said.
