<HEAD>Fog Grounds Medfly Spraying In Swank Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> took cover, but fog grounded the state's aerial insecticide attack on the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> fruit fly in the ritzy neighborhood and other areas where the crop-destroying pest has invaded. The postponement gave about 100,000 residents another day to protect their Porsches, Rolls Royces and expensive outdoor statuary against thousands of gallons of sticky mixture containing Malathion. The mission was rescheduled for 7 tonight. Some residents still doubted whether there has been sufficient notice, but one <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benz </ORGANIZATION> dealer evacuated his high-priced rolling stock into an underground parking garage and other car dealers looked for tarps. `` I'm surprised with the way they notified us,'' said resident <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>. `` The way they notified us has been so low-key that I question whether there has been adequate notification.'' Three helicopters scheduled to spray over a 35-square-mile area of homes and businesses west of downtown late Wednesday stayed at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after the fog rolled in from the ocean, officials said. `` It was just too dangerous to try it,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Donley </PERSON> at the state's Medfly Hotline. `` They want to try it earlier. The earlier they spray the better the chances they avoid the fog.'' The spraying was ordered because 40 Medflies were found in yards since Sept. 26, signaling a serious infestation that, if allowed to spread, could threaten <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s $ 8 billion in crops. The Medfly, a native to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and other tropical areas, is believed to be brought to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> unwittingly by tourists or on illegally transported fruit mailed from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. If the all-night, eight-hour spraying assault wipes out enough Medflies, officials will release sterile flies to breed with the surviving insects to render them sterile, <PERSON> Donley </PERSON> said. Most of the exclusive residential sections of <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, including the mansions of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s rich and famous, are spared of the spraying, but posh Rodeo Drive shops and many car dealerships are in the target area. The pesticide poses no health risks, officials say, but the sticky corn syrup bait mixed with the Malathion could mess up a car's paint job. Museums in the area covered their outdoor statues. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON>, who runs Scandinavian Auto Body in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, scrambled to find tarpaulins or garage space Wednesday for a fleet of <ORGANIZATION> Alfa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Romeos </ORGANIZATION>. `` You're looking at about $ 7,500 in refinishing that would have to be done,'' <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON> said. But Agricultural Commissioner <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Spaugy </PERSON> said the fight to save the state's farm industry knows no economic boundaries. `` We're encouraging people to cover up their Rolls Royces just like they would cover up their Pintos,'' he said. Along with parts of <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, officials are spraying the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> sections of <LOCATION> Culver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Palms, <LOCATION> Baldwin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. These communities all are dozens of miles from the nearest commercial crops, but the pest can spread rapidly. It lays its eggs under the skin of a wide variety of fruits and vegetables, hatching maggots that destroy the crop. The last serious infestation, in 1980 and 1981, cost <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> farmers an estimated $ 100 million.
