<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, but a big chunk of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> assembled in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> as <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s colleagues came to give reporters instant analyses of their vice presidential debate They said of the rivals things a senator normally never says about a senator. Things like: `` cheap shot,'' `` knockout blow,'' `` vicious'' and `` unbecoming.'' One senator said he was `` embarrassed'' for another. Protocol took a powder. It's not the way they talk back in the Capitol. More than two dozen lawmakers from both parties were flown in for the showdown on `` <LOCATION> Spin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alley </LOCATION>,'' the area of the press hall where campaign officials circulated to share with reporters their views of the debates in hopes of influencing what got said on the air or put in print. Each team had rented a charter to jet their players from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> for the night and they sent in so many that the spinners nearly crushed the press trying to write down their reactions. Most of them flowed in two streams, one from each party, that quickly filled the hall minutes after the contest ended. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign chairman, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, rated a briefing all his own outside the debate hall Before the debate, the two campaigns briefed the surrogates. Afterward, verdicts in hand, the responses were predictable, and they did n't always fit the decorum they practice in the Capitol. For the Democrats, the big topic was <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s assertion to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> that he was `` no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' `` I thought that was the knockout blow of the evening,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Ala