<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government says new safety guidelines for the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION> that makes radioactive material for nuclear arms were lost in `` paper work'' for a month last summer. During the delay, the plant operator waited 40 hours before notifying the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> of a small power surge that caused the shutdown of one of three atomic reactors at the plant, <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Craft </PERSON>, a department spokeswoman, said Wednesday. The delay violated both the new and the previous guidelines, she said, and efforts have been made to improve procedures. <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> is the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facility which produces weapons-grade plutonium and tritium. DOE and the E.I. du <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemours </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the plant under contract, have come under fire in recent days because of disclosures that during a 28-year period, up to 30 significant reactor mishaps there were not reported to the public and in some cases to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The power surge in August triggered a review by an internal <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> team which found the P reactor involved suffers from `` numerous and longstanding'' problems with its control rods _ which act as accelerators and brakes on a reactor's rate of fission _ that may prevent operators from recognizing potentially dangerous conditions in its core, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported today. `` Technical support personnel stated they routinely calculate core reactivity assuming seven rods are not in their programmed positions,'' the team's report said, according to The Post. The newspaper said it obtained a copy of the study, which has not been released publicly. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in today's editions that a study by a consulting firm of the plant's operations from 1971-1987 shows that chronic equipment failure and poor operating procedures caused nuclear reactors there to shut down unexpectedly nine to 12 times a year for nearly two decades. That rate is twice that of the civilian nuclear power industry, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Starostecki </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION>'s chief safety operator, told the newspaper that civilian reactors with the same number of forced shutdowns would have had their operating licenses revoked. Meanwhile, an internal memorandum about a May 10, 1965 accident at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plant said a supervisor had to stop a foreman from taking action that could have turned a leak of cooling water into a catastrophic accident, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported from <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, near where the plant is located. `` One trained man stood between us and disaster,'' said the memo written by a <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> engineer, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON>, in 1981 when he took early retirement. <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON> had been in the reactor control room when the incident occurred. A technical supervisor at the plant, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merz </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in an interview Wednesday that this was `` a premature conclusion.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, in an internal report obtained by the The State of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, criticized <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>'s management as isolated and said the plant is operated counter to `` practices common to well-run nuclear plants.'' The 50-page draft memorandum criticized `` less than precise and out-of-date operating practices'' throughout the plant's management and reactor staff, the newspaper reported today. Written by a panel of <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION> officials and represenatives from companies working at the plant, the report criticized <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> and <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> for allowing reactor operators to grow complacent. It called for streamlined communications and better training to handle emergencies. As part of an effort to improve safety and reporting procedures at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, Energy Undersecretary <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> issued a new order on June 21 requiring the contractor and the regional <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> office, in <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION> to notify the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> headquarters immediately in the event of a safety problem. The notice did not reach the mailroom of the regional office until July 7, nearly three weeks after it was issued. And it took another month to reach the appropriate office in <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, said Ms. Craft. The regional department office asked for clarification from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and did not send the new guidance to <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> until Aug. 23, she said. In the meantime there was another mishap, a small power pulse on Aug. 7 which caused the reactor to be shut down on Aug. 9. Since the incident in August, said Ms. Craft, `` we have worked with du <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> to correct any deficiencies that we had. There are several programs that du <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> has put in place to prevent this from occurring in the future,'' she said. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> spokesmen did not immediately return telephone calls to their offices in <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>.
