<FIRST>u i PM-Burma-Defeat     10-06 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma-Defeat,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vicious Cycle: Burma Chases Its Tail</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After lurching through bloodshed and political upheaval, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> is almost back to where it was 11 weeks ago: with an authoritarian government and few prospects for the democracy that once seemed so close. Since the resignation of strongman Ne Win on July 23, several thousand people have died, hundreds of thousands marched in the streets in a nationwide uprising and three leaders took turns at the helm. Now, some Western experts say the best hope for the pro-democracy forces is that the government will offer political and economic liberalization to appease an angry population. Pressure for change, they say, may also come from <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s vital foreign aid donors. `` Given all that's happened, it's silly to write the opposition off, but overall I think the army is sitting squarely on top of the people for at least the next few weeks,'' said a Western diplomat in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. The recent chaotic events amounted to the largest anti-government movement in the past 26 years of autocratic rule and the most intense and widespread display of `` people power'' since the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> fight for independence from <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. But the ruling oligarchy of military men around Ne Win, despite earlier rumors that they were about to flee the country, dug in, maneuvered with what some analysts say was `` Machiavellian brilliance'' and at the very least temporarily won the day. As the drama unfolded, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> experts offered a number of possible scenarios, including one that called for the military to shoot as many protestors as necessary to retain power. This is the option it chose, together with what one Western ambassador in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> described as a `` devilish plot'' of stoking chaos and anxiety among masses who grew increasingly short of food, fuel and other necessities. `` The people have been beaten over the head for two months. They never got weapons and they were never really organized _ and the army never cracked,'' said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> scholar <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverstein </PERSON>. Although the government has promised general elections, a key opposition leader, former defense minister Tin Oo, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>: `` All the opposition leaders are now facing arrest and other punitive measures. So what can I say? The situation is so undemocratic.'' Opponents appear to have little maneuvering room. Their major weapon, a general strike that began Aug. 8, was blunted when civil servants and factory workers threatened by dismissal returned to their jobs Oct. 3. Rather than a single, united opposition, at least four anti-government parties have emerged while the more radical students, who spearheaded the demonstrations, are fleeing to the Thai-Burmese border to get guerrilla training from ethnic minority rebels. By contrast, the conservative party has the benefit of big coffers, a nationwide network built up over 26 years and a body of loyalists who stand to lose sizable perks should the opposition win. Despite efforts to officially divorce the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> from the government, analysts agree it is a major instrument of the military-backed leadership. Prior to the current upheavals the party, then known as the <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, claimed that more than 14 million out of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s 38 million people were members of either the party or its affiliates. <PERSON> Silverstein </PERSON> and others say the leadership's weak spot is the shattered economy and dependence on foreign aid to mount a revival. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which supplies about 80 percent of foreign loans and grants, and other donors have frozen assistance but whether <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> choses to use its considerable clout to shape events inside <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> remains uncertain. `` This is a lever the military has to cope with. If anything can now leverage the situation it's going to be the need for outside assistance,'' <PERSON> Silverstein </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 __ EDITORS'S NOTE _ <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> is <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> bureau </ORGANIZATION> chief in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> and has traveled to <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> numerous times.
