<TEXT>
 A federal judge has sealed a jury's verdict in a $ 1.5 million damage suit against the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> while he considers a city council member's decision to withdraw as the chief plaintiff. In a rambling explanation to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moye </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, longtime civil rights activist and City Councilman <PERSON> Hosea </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said Wednesday he had lost sleep worrying about the blue-collar defendants `` who have nothing but their homes, their cars and their paychecks. ... I could not disrupt their families.'' The suit seeks $ 1 million in punitive damages against two <ORGANIZATION> KKK </ORGANIZATION> groups as corporations. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Dees </PERSON> also asked the jury to return heavy individual damages: $ 200,000 against <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>, grand dragon of the Southern White Knights; and $ 100,000 each against <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Carver </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> grand dragon of the Invisible Empire; the group's former grand dragon, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON>, a veteran of several white supremacist groups and an associate of <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>'s. But state Rep. <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, D-Atlanta, who joined the lawsuit in July, objected to <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' attempt to halt the trial, resulting in a hectic day of legal maneuvering while jurors were deliberating a verdict. The suit charged that leaders of the Klan groups conspired to disrupt a Jan. 17, 1987, `` brotherhood march'' by civil rights activists in <LOCATION> Forsyth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and violate the marchers' civil rights. Participants in the march were pelted with rocks, bottles and other debris thrown from people who were among a large group of counterdemonstrators who gathered in the virtually all-white county north of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. A week later, more than 20,000 people descended upon <LOCATION> Forsyth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in a huge civil rights march that drew national attention. <PERSON> Moye </PERSON> ordered that the verdict, delivered to the courtroom shortly before 5 p.m., be sealed in an envelope. He dismissed the six jurors with orders that they not discuss their verdict with anyone. He did not tell them why their verdict was sealed. <PERSON> Moye </PERSON> ordered a hearing today with <PERSON> Dees </PERSON>, who brought the lawsuit on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> and 55 other marchers pelted with rocks and bottles; and attorneys for the two <ORGANIZATION> KKK </ORGANIZATION> organizations, their leaders and other defendants. <PERSON> Moye </PERSON> did not discuss the subject of the hearing, but defense attorneys told the court they will file motions to reopen the trial in order to question <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>. The jury, which included one black member, began its deliberations at Wednesday morning. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said he was torn by conscience as a believer in `` redemption'' and `` forgiving your enemies,'' saying <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> and the late <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> would approve. Defense attorney <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON> said it was a `` noble, chivalrous and Christian gesture.''
