<FIRST>u i PM-DelaMadrid     10-06 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-De la Madrid,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Industrialized Countries Beginning to Understand
Debt Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> says there are `` slight and tenuous signs'' that the industrialized countries are beginning to understand the problem of the debt owed them by developing nations. The question is whether that understanding will lead to solutions to the problem, the outgoing president said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> also said that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will respond to the stronger showing by opposition parties in July 6 general elections and become a `` more democratic country.'' De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, 54, leaves office Dec. 1. His Institutional Revolutionary Party has governed <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since 1929 and will continue to do so under president-elect <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>. De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> has been a leader in demanding better debt payment conditions for the Third World but at the same time has maintained <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s commitment to pay. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has renegotiated its debt and made service payments of more than $ 75 billion in the past six years that <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION> has been president. But the principal is $ 104 billion, a few billion more than when de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> took office. Pointing to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> as an example, de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> said debtor nations must `` set our house in order internally'' with economic measures and `` demand at the same time a fair and realistic deal from creditors.'' He said some world leaders and banks now realize that the debt affects the entire world economy. `` <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> insists on joint responsibility of debtor and creditor for the debt,'' he said. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> must `` modernize while retaining its principles but become more efficient'' in working with the grass-roots membership. However, the opposition leftist and rightist parties also `` must realize the times they live in and update their ideology, change tactics and present articulate programs to the people,'' he said. He said the `` relative strengthening of the opposition is a small price to pay for the strengthening of political pluralism.'' Political reforms de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> initiated led to greater opposition representation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Relaxed and smiling easily during the interview, de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> recalled that when he took office the country had just $ 100 million in reserves. Citizens were disenchanted with a political system, which though stable, was fraught with corruption. The world oil price collapse had shattered Mexican dreams of abundance of citizens told two years earlier that they were on their way to prosperity. There is general agreement that the stocky, unpretentious president who dealt out strong economic medicine held together a country on the verge of social conflict six years ago. `` The most serious problem at the time was the lack of confidence of Mexicans in themselves and the conflict between social groups. My concern was to maintain peace and individual freedoms while trying to obtain a social consensus,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION> enacted measures that eliminated many subsidies. Prices went up and salaries lost more than half their buying power. He was accused of favoring the elite. Through the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> dominance of labor unions, he kept protests down and eventually got labor, government and private business to agree on a wage and price control plan that reduced inflation to an estimated 50 percent for this year, down from 159.2 percent in 1987. De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> brought <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> into the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs, opening <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s markets and forcing its manufacturers to compete. The manufacturing industry's exports in 1972 paid for only 26 percent of its imports. In 1987, they paid for 98 percent of the imports. International dollar reserves climbed to $ 15 billion this year as non-oil exports made up for the large drop in petroleum income. `` I am satisfied that some progress was made,'' de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> said. But he acknowledged things will not be easy for <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
