<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New Yorkers already accustomed to subway ads for hemorrhoid ointments, roach killers and AIDS prevention will see a graphic ad opposing aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> that had been rejected here and elsewhere as inflammatory. The advertisement shows a photograph of a dead man lying in a pool of blood on a Salvadoran street. `` What are your tax dollars buying in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>?'' it asks. The company that controls subway ad contracts for the city had rejected it last spring on the grounds that it was `` inflammatory'' and `` offensive.'' The ad finally went up in every fourth subway car this week after the organization behind it threatened legal action and the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> decided the ad did not violate its standards of good taste. The ad is sponsored by Winning Democracy in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based coalition of organizations that opposes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. All told, producing and renting the space for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ad is costing Winning Democracy about $ 20,000, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Elia </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> spokesman for the group. The coalition is placing similar ads in buses and subways throughout the country. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, the ads are due in a month or two. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, they will be going up this week. They are up already in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The company that arranges ad contracts for <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' buses has so far refused to accept the ads, said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PER