RGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> studied medicine at <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and received his medical degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION>. In 1933, he and two other doctors went to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> to study tropical medicine. <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for the rest of his life. `` All around me were poverty, malnutrition and exploitation,'' <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> said in a 1983 interview. `` I found the social evils of old <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were more fatal to the poor than illness. The problem was not only medical but political.'' <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> said in 1984 that he first read <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>'s Communist Manifesto in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>: `` Its impact on me was immediate. I thought then, and think now, that the poorer you are, the more easily you understand the Manifesto. In 1936, <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>, the journalist-author of the classic `` Red Star over <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' answered <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s call for a `` Western-trained doctor and an honest journalist.'' They made their way through Nationalist lines to join the Communists in their northwestern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> stronghold. For the next 13 years, until the Communist triumph, <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> served as medical adviser to the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. In 1950, <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> became the first non-Chinese citizen of the new <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He took on the Chinese name of <PERSON> Ma </PERSON> <PERSON> Haide </PERSON>. <PERSON> Haide </PERSON> means `` virtue from across the seas.'' In 1953, <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> helped organize the Dermatology