<HEAD>Medvedev Endorses Importing of Economic Ideas from West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s new ideology chief said socialism must learn from the West and try the kind of bold economic experiments President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has proposed. In his first major speech since being catapulted onto the ruling Politburo, <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said some of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms have fostered abuses, but in general he showed himself a closer ally of the Soviet leader than his predecessor as ideology chief, <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>. Some Western diplomatic analysists had predicted <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, seen as a reform economist, would be charged with redefining socialism to incorporate <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s pragmatic approach to rebuilding the Soviet economy. His remarks, published Wednesday in the newspapers Pravda and <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, appeared to begin that process. But he took a cautious first step. `` Unfortunately, there have been some irresponsible attempts to cast a shadow over <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s inheritance, over the basic values of socialism,'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said. `` And how else can those statements appearing in the press be interpreted that claim that the command-administrative system resulted from <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, those attempts to deny the socialist nature of our system, that even doubt the rightness of our choice for socialism?'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, 59, a political economist by training, was named to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> on Friday by the party's policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and was named to head a newly created commission on ideology He spoke Tuesday to an international conference in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on the problems of contemporary socialism. In his reported remarks, <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> showed himself more open to following the Western example to help solve Soviet problems than was <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, the Politburo member reputed to be a conservative opponent of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. But some Soviets who read <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>'s speech in the national press said it was impossible to conclude that the newest Politburo member had completely embraced <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform agenda. The party's new ideology chief spoke of the need for `` deep qualitative rejuvenation'' in socialism, and said the solution to some Soviet problems could come from other socialist countries, and even from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. `` While the socialist perspective is being worked out, the experience of humanity as a whole can not be ignored, including the non-socialist part of the world,'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said. `` I'm referring not only to the scientific and technical achievements of the system that is opposed to us, but to many forms of organization of public life, of the economic process.'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> also urged a rethinking of the role of central planning and the market, and voiced support for two pillars of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program for `` perestroika,'' or nationwide restructuring: leasing farmland to individual farmers and spreading economic cooperatives to provide consumer goods that are lacking in the state sector <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, in an Aug. 5 speech, said the class struggle determines international relations. But <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> hewed more closely to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s line, which maintains that in the nuclear age, East and West must cooperate to solve common problems. `` The conception is outdated that socialism and capitalism can develop in a parallel way,'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said. `` On the contrary, their ways will inevitably intersect, both systems will inevitably interact within the framework of the same human civilization.''
