<DATELINE>NOVI SAD, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The communist leadership of the northern province of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> said today it will resign. The announcement came after 50,000 people rallied to demand the ouster of the politicians in a deepening economic crisis. <PERSON> Milovan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sogorov </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vojvodina </ORGANIZATION>, made the announcement in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> at an emergency session of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Serbia </ORGANIZATION>, which controls the autonomous northern province, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was to implement the resignations at an emergency meeting this evening in this provincial capital, about 40 miles north of <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, state television reported. The resignation could pave the way for wholesale changes in the national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership and in the parties of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six constituent republics. Angry crowds in Novi Sad chanted `` We want resignations!'' as they gathered in front of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. The state news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> estimated the crowds at 100,000, but an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter at the scene estimated about 50,000 people were on the streets at midafternoon. The protesters tried to force their way into the party headquarters, but cordons of police, including a riot unit, blocked their way. The crowds then moved to a larger square. Loudspeakers broadcast shouted slogans about <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s growing problems, which includes 217 percent inflation, a 15 percent unemployment rate and a $ 21 billion foreign debt. The flag-waving demonstrators chanted `` Police go away!'' `` We are going to smash windows!'' and `` We want freedom!'' and demanded the immediate resignation of the provincial Communist leadership, according to the witnesses. Communist officials who spoke were booed and jeered by the crowd, and television showed one hit with a bottle. Most factories and businesses in the city remained closed. The Serbian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement after its emergency meeting saying the political situation in <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> was deteriorating rapidly, according to <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> leadership has been deaf to the demands of the working class and other citizens,'' the statement said, adding, `` a serious split has occurred between the <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> leadership and the people.'' The demonstrations in Novi Sad began about noon Wednesday and continued into the night. Protesters also chanted in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Serbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who is demanding that the republic of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> be given stronger central authority over <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, a second autonomous region under <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. Serbs claim ethnic Albanians, who form a majority of the population of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, are forcing them out of the southern province. The protests in <LOCATION> Vojvodina </