<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> police officer testified today that a man accused of taking 110 people hostage at a private school was armed with a rifle every time he saw him through the front door of the building. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, the defendant who is representing himself at his trial on kidnapping charges, asked Capt. <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON> whether he saw <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> ever point the weapon at children inside <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> End </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION>. `` Not directly at them, but you had it ready,'' Fields said. The defendant then asked him whether he thought <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s life might have been in danger and whether that could have been the reason he had the weapon. Fields said that could have been the case. In his opening statement to the jury Wednesday, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, 43, defended his takeover of the school on Feb. 2 by saying the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution gives him the right to bear arms. `` I did n't kidnap anybody,'' the unemployed <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> resident told jurors. `` I went there to exercise my constitutional rights. The government is doing things to destroy the future of our country.'' <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> has said he took over the school to call attention to the homeless and hungry in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. His trial was moved to <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> because of publicity in <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION>. He began his defense after District Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> told the jury that `` children and teachers were in stark, cold terror for endless hours'' during the incident. The 110 counts involve 104 students, five teachers and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERS