<HEAD>Writer Geoffrey Household Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Household </PERSON>, whose adventure novels include the tale of an English hunter who stalks <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, is dead at age 87, his family said Thursday. The writer's home was near <LOCATION> Banbury </LOCATION>, 65 miles from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The family said he died Tuesday, and no cause of death was given. Household said the story of an attempt to kill <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> came to him because `` the man had to be dealt with and I began to think how much I would love to kill him.'' The hero of `` Rogue Male,'' published in 1939, is an aristocratic big-game hunter who is caught and tortured by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> but escapes. During World War II, Household served as a commando in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and later as an intelligence officer in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. He was educated at <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, then traveled and worked at various jobs in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Near </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He used the impressions gained from his travels in his novels. A magazine financed him to write the `` The Third Hour,'' a novel published in 1937. His first book of short stories, `` The Salvation of <PERSON> Pisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabar </PERSON>,'' appeared in 1938. Household resumed writing after the war, producing adventure stories with such titles as `` A Rough Shoot'' in 1951 and `` Watcher in the Shadows'' in 1960. He also wrote picaresque romances, children's books, stories about the supernatural and an autobiography, `` Against The Wind,'' published in 1958. Surviving are his wife, <PERSON> Ilona </PERSON> <PERSON> Zsoldos-Gutman </PERSON>, a son and two daughters.
