<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Children     10-06 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Children,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Care for AIDS Children Tops $90,000, Much Unnecessary:
Studies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Children infected with the virus that causes AIDS are running up hospital bills of more than $ 90,000 each, often because they simply have nowhere else to go, studies indicate. `` Many of these children are in the hospital not because they're sick with AIDS or with anything else,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Kathi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemper </PERSON>, who examined cases of children testing positive for evidence of AIDS infection at <LOCATION> Yale-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> `` But because they test positive, nobody wants to take care of them at home or in foster care, and so there's no place else for them to go,'' she said in a telephone interview Thursday. `` Basically, they're in the hospital like a day-care center.'' Home lives of such babies tend to be chaotic because the mothers who transmitted the virus to them usually are intravenous drug abusers, often sick themselves and possibly in jail, researchers said. A significant number of babies who test positive are n't even infected _ they simply are carrying AIDS antibodies they inherited from their mothers, said Ms. <PERSON> Kemper </PERSON>, now with <ORGANIZATION> Harborview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. AIDS antibodies _ natural disease-fighting agents produced by a person's system in the face of AIDS infection _ fade from uninfected babies' bloodstreams by age 6 months to 15 months, she said All AIDS tests in current use detect antibodies to the virus, rather than the virus itself. Even youngsters who really are sick often are put in the hospital or kept there unnecessarily, Ms. <PERSON> Kemper </PERSON> said. `` Some of them easily could be getting treatment on an outpatient basis.'' Yet potential foster families often fear they might catch AIDS _ a remote possibility _ and insurance and Medicaid policies are set up to reimburse for hospital care more efficiently than for outpatient or home care, she said. By Sept. 26, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> had recorded 1,185 cases of AIDS among children under age 13, of whom 672 had died. Medical researchers have estimated that 10,000 children could be infected by 1991. The study by Ms. <PERSON> Kemper </PERSON> and colleague <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Forsyth </PERSON>, published in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, looked at children who had tested positive for AIDS antibodies at <LOCATION> Yale-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> through Oct. 31, 1987. `` Among children eligible for the study, 54 percent of their hospital days were judged medically unnecessary,'' the study said. The most common non-medical reason for hospitalization was lack of any other place to send the child, it said. A related study in Friday's Journal found that hospital stays for children infected with the AIDS virus ranged from $ 466 per day for `` boarder babies'' _ those who simply had nowhere else to go _ to $ 705 per day for the sickest youngsters. That study, led by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hegarty </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Harlem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, looked at 37 children diagnosed with AIDS or an AIDS-related condition in that hospital from 1981 through 1986. `` Average lifetime costs were $ 90,347 per child,'' the study said. `` One third of the total inpatient days and over 20 percent of the cost resulted from social rather than medical factors.'' Ms. <PERSON> Kemper </PERSON> called for better education and better reimbursement for potential foster parents and modified policies under the Medicaid program and private insurance plans. She noted that <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> waged a foster-parent education campaign and boosted reimbursement to $ 1,000 a month for foster families, helping reduce the rate of unnecessary hospital days from 64 percent in 1983 and 1984 to 30 percent in 1987 for the children studied.
