<HEAD>House Passes Legislation to End US Trusteeship Over Palau</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday passed legislation designed to end the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' trusteeship over <ORGANIZATION> Palau </ORGANIZATION>, the last western <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island nation still covered by the trusteeships set up by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in 1947. The bill, sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by a 406-11 vote, would authorize the president to enter into a compact of free association with <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> once the <LOCATION> Micronesian </LOCATION> nation of 14,000 people approves the plan. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> is a strategically important area that could host <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military and naval bases if a new defense basing agreement can not be worked out with the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Under the proposed compact, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would gain basing rights in <LOCATION> Palau </LOCATION> and would be responsible for defending the islands. The future of the legislation was uncertain as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> worked toward adjournment next week. A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said key members of the panel are opposed to the plan drafted by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s insular and territorial affairs subcommittee The aide said the main problem involves about $ 40 million in assistance to <LOCATION> Palau </LOCATION> proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in addition