<HEAD>Senators Seek Independent Probe of Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four senators on Thursday asked an independent committee to review safety and operations at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> facility that produces nuclear weapons material. The plant, run by E.I. du <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemours </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> under contract from the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, has come under increasing scrutiny since disclosures last week that as many as 30 major mishaps there over three decades had not been reported to department headquarters or disclosed to the public. The alleged questionable safety and operating procedures, detailed in internal documents from <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> and the department, continued until this August, when the latest incident caused engineers to shut down the P-Reactor at the plant. The facility's other two reactors also have been shut down `` We are very concerned about both the August 1988 incident at P-Reactor and earlier incidents discussed in a recently disclosed 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> memorandum,'' said the letter, signed by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore They called for an investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION>, which is headed <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> and was established by Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> to give independent assessments of operations at nuclear facilities. <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> expressed concern over the failure of <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials to notify him during the August incident, according to detailed report on the mishap released Thursday by the department. The report concluded that despite a power pulse, `` there was no accident, no near-miss, and the reactor was not out of control.'' `` The decision was made to shut down P-Reactor, a strategic defense facility, even though no imminent safety hazard was present,'' said the report, prepared by a committee headed by <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamric </PERSON>, assistant manager for projects at the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The report found that engineers starting P-Reactor on Aug. 7 miscalculated the amount of xenon and tritium in the reactor and used an unorthodox method of adjusting two of the rods used to control the nuclear reaction. The reactor experienced a small power pulse, or `` blip,'' the next day. The reactor was shut down on Aug. 17 under orders from officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. A detailed analysis disclosed that `` two full weak control rods -LRB- 35A and 53F -RRB- were found to be at their full up position when they should have been fully inserted,'' the <PERSON> Hamric </PERSON> report said. `` No reason nor accurate time for the occurrence was annotated in the operating logs.'' As a fix, operators `` drove rods 35A and 53F back to their original positions by using ... a device for positioning single rods by bypassing their normal control signal path,'' the report said. ` A concise and clear log entry was not made,'' it said. `` Such joint movement of control rods had never previously been seen by this operating shift, but restart continued normally.'' A spokesman for <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> said company officials had not yet seen the <PERSON> Hamric </PERSON> report but have moved to correct some of the deficiencies. `` Some of these problems have been identified,'' spokesman <PERSON> Clif </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said. `` We have been thinking about making these changes for some time.'' <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON>, head of the independent committee, was informed of the unusual procedures not by Du Pont or <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials, but by a newspaper reporter who called him on Aug. 16, the report said, and he `` was surprised to learn of the situation at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>.'' The following morning, <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> sent a request by telecopier asking du Pont and <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for full information, the report said. <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> was out his office Thursday and did not respond to inquiries from The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
