<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Health officials will vaccinate every Israeli up to the age of 40 against polio following an outbreak of the disease that affected at least nine people, the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday. About 3.2 million residents will be innoculated, and the program should be completed in a month, ministry spokesman <PERSON> Shmuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Algrabli </PERSON> said. It will cost about $ 3.1 million. `` We hope this will help to calm people down,'' <PERSON> Algrabli </PERSON> said. `` We are calling on the public not to panic and not to try to be innoculated privately. There is enough vaccine in the country for everyone.'' The government undertook the campaign after hearing recommendations from a team of international health experts called to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for consultations after nine patients were diagnosed with polio, <PERSON> Algrabli </PERSON> said. There are another three unconfirmed cases of the disease, he said. The outbreak of polio, thought to be wiped out in the country, was a surprise to Israelis, who are innoculated rountinely as infants. The new vaccination is an additional booster. Polio is an infectious disease caused by a virus inflammation of the gray matter of the spinal cord. It is accompanied by paralysis of various muscle groups. Just weeks before the Israeli polio cases were reported last month, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, to which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> belongs, was considering declaring the disease eradicated in the region. No cases were reported in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> last year and only one case was reported in 1986. The recent cases have been blamed on overflowing sewage. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s health officials are now considering changing the method of routine childhood vaccination from the live-virus <P