legislative session, will help `` put it first in line so they ca n't shove it aside'' next year The Office of Technology Assessment has estimated that screening women over 65 could reduce the breast cancer mortality rate by 50 percent after five years, according to Mrs. <PERSON> Kennelly </PERSON>. `` Breast cancer took the lives of 45,000 women in 1987, of which 28,000 were over age 65. Many of those lives could have been saved if mammograms were readily available and affordable to those women,'' she said at a news conference. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> recommends that women over 40 undergo mammography screenings annually.
