</PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> vetoed the idea, said <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, a historian at the Kennedy Library. Since 1963, the issue of a total ban has arisen several times, but the superpowers have never agreed. <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said the Oval Office tapes included no dramatic revelations but supplied a close-up look at the treaty process. `` It's a mixture of so many different levels of concern: constitutional, diplomatic, political, personal,'' <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said. The tapes reveal that <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was well aware of the sales job he faced to win a two-thirds ratification vote in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, and he made sure to enlist former Presidents <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>. In July, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> spoke with Secretary of State Dean <PERSON> Rusk </PERSON> and proposed giving a presidential speech in favor of the treaty. `` We got to hit the country while the country's hot. That's the only thing that makes any impression to these goddamned senators,'' said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who had left the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> himself just 2 -LCB- years earlier.
