RGANIZATION>, the nation's clearinghouse and response center for hazardous material emergencies, when the troubles began at the plant. A minor fire at the plant was controlled on the morning of June 17, but firefighters were called back to the scene that night when a police officer spotted flames inside the building. The subsequent blaze, fed by thousands of exploding barrels of chloride tablets, took four days to get under control. At its height it sent up a cloud of poisonous chlorine gas three miles long, 100 feet high and four blocks wide. More than 200 people were treated at local hospitals for minor injuries from the fumes. Officials estimate that 180,000 gallons of chlorine leaked. `` In light of the magnitude of the release and its impact on the <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> community, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> considers the violations particularly egregious,'' <LOCATION> Deland </LOCATION> said. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON>, attorney for the company, said it will probably contest the fine and he questioned its severity, maintaining the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> `` in reality knew about this leak from the start.'' He also said the city must prove the company was negligent before it can collect damages. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> fine is based only on the company's failure to provide a written report to date on what chemicals spilled, how much was released and other information. An <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> attorney maintained the agency was summoned to the scene by state officials, not company executives, 15 hours after the incident began. The state's private cleanup contractor is also trying to recoup the cost of the cleanup, estimated at a minimum of $ 500,000. Residents and local business firms in the evacuated areas also have filed class-action suits against the company, which lawyers said could reach into the millions of dollars.
