<HEAD>Labor Reaffirms Nuclear Policy, Embarrassing Kinnock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> reaffirmed its policy of unilateral nuclear disarmament Thursday, rejecting party leader <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON>'s attempt to soften a position that has been unpopular with British voters. Labor's annual conference endorsed a resolution stipulating that a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> government would scrap <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s nuclear weapons and close <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear bases in this country during its first five-year term. It carried by 480,000 votes in a total of nearly 6 million, much closer than previous ballots on an issue that has divided the party for decades. Union leaders cast huge block votes at annual conferences based on their memberships. <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> supported a resolution that said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s nuclear weapons could be used as a bargaining chip with the Soviets and did not set a time limit. He indicated the socialist party's leadership might ignore the vote in drawing up the nuclear weapons platform during a policy review to be completed next year. `` Today's votes ... were not conclusive,'' he told reporters Thursday night. `` It is our duty to get a defense and nuclear disarmament policy which can enjoy the support and confidence of the people of this country.'' <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Livingstone </PERSON>, a leader of the Labor left, warned <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON>: `` If you try and ditch this policy there will be civil war in this party.'' The defeat marked the most serious split at the conference between <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> and a left wing dismayed by <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s shift to the center after three election losses to the Conservatives. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, with 1.25 million members, led opposition to what he called the `` confusion and fudge'' of the <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> resolution. It sought to keep the party's options open by calling for disarmament by `` unilateral, bilateral and multilateral means.'' <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaufman </PERSON>, party spokesman on foreign affairs, said in debate that an unconditional disarmament policy would `` mark the end of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s role in world nuclear disarmament.'' `` The question is not whether a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Britain </ORGANIZATION> would go non-nuclear ... but how we go non-nuclear,'' he said. Labor adopted the unilateral nuclear disarmament policy in 1981, two years after losing power to <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and her Conservatives. Polls indicate it was a major factor in the party's subsequent defeats <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON>, a lifelong campaigner against nuclear weapons, has shifted his stance in the past 18 months and now argues that the U.S.-Soviet agreement to destroy medium-range nuclear missiles has created a climate for negotiation. The superpower agreement does not affect <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s nuclear weapons, submarine-carried <ORGANIZATION> Polaris </ORGANIZATION> missiles that will be replaced in the 1990s by more potent Trident missiles Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has bought from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Nuclear-capable American F-111 bombers also are deployed at two British bases and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Poseidon </LOCATION> submarines, equipped with nuclear arms, operate from Holy Loch, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>.
