<FIRST>u i AM-Chile-Future Bjt   10-06 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Future, Bjt,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Facing Daunting Challenge After Pinochet's Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Chilean opposition, buoyed by its ballot-box defeat of military President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, now faces the challenge of maintaining its new-found unity in advance of open elections. In addition, potentially divisive issues such as human rights trials and the future of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> could sow dissent as opposition leaders pursue talks with the armed forces to speed the transition to full democracy. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> lost a plebiscite Wednesday on a proposal for him to remain in power until 1997. According to the 1980 constitution pushed through by the 72-year-old army commander's administration, open presidential elections will be held in December 1989. Furher negotiations between the military government and the opposition hinge on <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s standing with his troops, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and expert on <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> and Latin American authoritarian governments. `` I think it depends on whether the referendum loss officially discredits him within his own service,'' <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> to observe the voting, said during a telephone interview. <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON> said the navy, air force and national police appear more willing to negotiate than <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s army, which has been fervently loyal to its chief. `` They are more flexible,'' <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON> said of the navy, air force and national police. `` They've been predicting this'' defeat. Political maneuvering by top opposition figures for nomination to the presidency also is expected to influence relations within the 16 parties that formed a coalition to lead the anti-Pinochet campaign. <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON> said he expected <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, Socialist leader of the center-left <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> alliance </ORGANIZATION>, to run for the presidency along with someone who will represent the political right. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> helped lead the coalition, created early this year after years of bitter feuding among the opposition. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> often played on those divisions to strengthen his rule. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> insisted after the vote that unity must be maintained, and even expanded to include groups on the right and left who had been excluded in the past. `` We do n't want there to be winner and losers,'' <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> said. `` To the contrary, everyone must collaborate in the reconstruction of the country.'' `` The armed forces have an important role to play,'' <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> added. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>' moderate leftist stance offends many conservatives, and he has hinted at a willingness to put aside presidential ambitions in the interest of a smooth transition of power. Asked if the pro-Moscow Communist Party should be included, <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> said all democratic parties to the right and the left should be embraced. `` There should be no exclusions,'' <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> said. Some leftist groups in the coalition favor including the Communists. However, the armed forces are fiercely anti-communist, and the 1980 constitution outlaws communist groups and the propagation of Marxist ideas. They are certain to reject the notion of sitting down at the bargaining table with anyone associated with communists. Leftist parties also are calling for justice in human rights abuse cases. More than 700 people disappeared and thousands have allegedly been tortured by security forces under <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, especially in the aftermath of the 1973 coup that brought him to power, rights groups say. Parties of the political right and center, apparently recognizing the military's fear of rights trials, have approached the issue with caution. They routinely say only that `` the truth must be known,'' implying an investigation should be conducted but not necessarily a trial involving military figures. The constitution also calls for a congress to be elected in a year but its provisions make virtually impossible any amendments. Observers believe the opposition's priority will be to ease the procedure for amending the document, leaving other, more specific changes for later. Leftist parties want it amended immediately to allow for quick elections and <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s rapid exit from the presidency. But <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> indicated his party was in no such hurry. `` The period could be six months, nine months, or a year,'' <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Noblet </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, is The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> bureau chief for <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>.
