<FIRST>r a AM-AssemblyLine     10-06 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Assembly Line,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assembly Line Marks 75th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The assembly line, which propelled <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> into automaking and industrial history, celebrates its 75th anniversary this week. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> planned a ceremony for Friday at its Wayne assembly plant. There, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s great-grandson, <PERSON> Edsel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> II, will ride off the modern-day assembly line in a Model T. In remarks prepared for Friday's events, <ORGANIZATION> Edsel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, general sales manager of the company's <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln-Mercury </ORGANIZATION> division, said that as in his great-grandfather's time, the company still is striving for quality and efficiency. `` Seventy-five years ago, my great-grandfather and his associates put in place the mechanism to realize his dream of building an affordable motor car for ` the great multitude' using the best employees and materials,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said. Production of the famous Model T began in mid-1908, and quickly, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> was determined to bring down the price of his product. Three-quarters of a century ago, and a few miles away from the sprawling <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> assembly plant, workers at a Ford plant in <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> were tinkering with an idea that would revolutionize manufacturing worldwide. On April Fools' Day, 1913, an engineer in the plant's flywheel-magneto assembly area tried out a new assembly technique that spread quickly to other component operations Then on Oct. 7, 1913, the entire process was transferred to the final assembly area. The first Model Ts to be built by the process were dragged by rope through the area as 150 workers stood in place, attaching components to the frame as it passed. Within a few years, the technique was adopted by a wide range of manufacturers. Nowadays, robots have taken the place of some workers and cars along the assembly line are raised, lowered and tilted to make access for workers easier. But amid the high technology, the car moves past the worker much in the same way it did 75 years ago.
</TEXT>
