 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s fever subsided Thursday after he received his daily blood transfusion. Palace doctors were quoted earlier as expressing fear that numerous transfusions in the past two weeks, already totaling more blood than the frail, 87-year-old monarch normally has in his body, were increasing <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s fever and pulse rate. He received 0.4 pints ofblood Thursday morning to compensate for continued internal bleeding, palace spokesman <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said, and has received 12 pints in the past 14 days. His temperature settled back to 99.3 Thursday evening from 100.9 hours earlier, <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said. The world's longest-reigning monarch has been bedridden since internal hemorrhaging caused him to cough up blood Sept. 19. He is being fed intravenously.
