<HEAD>Woman Arrested for Tuberculosis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A little-used law allowed police to arrest a woman who refused to be treated for tuberculosis and was believed to have spread the disease to family members, officials said Thursday. <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, 29, of <LOCATION> Suitland </LOCATION>, was arrested Wednesday by the Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and taken to <ORGANIZATION> Montebello </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, a state institution in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. She was in satisfactory condition Thursday and was expected to remain there for three to six months, a hospital spokesman said. Dr. <PERSON> Elin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gursky </PERSON>, director of epidemiology and disease control for the Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>, said Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> was arrested under a little-used provision of state law that allows public health officials to control the spread of contagious diseases. Tuberculosis, which is marked by coughing, night sweats and weight loss, can be cured, but can be fatal if left untreated, <PERSON> Gursky </PERSON> said. Health officials can not force <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> to receive treatment, but they can incarcerate her to prevent her from spreading it to others, <PERSON> Gursky </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> was described as being in a highly infectious stage of the disease, and could be jailed if she leaves the hospital, <PERSON> Gursky </PERSON> said. Several members of her family have tested positive for tuberculosis, and are expected to receive treatment, <PERSON> Gursky </PERSON> said. The criminal warrant was issued in July, after health officials failed to find her to serve a civil injunction issued in Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Matz </PERSON>, an assistant attorney general with the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and Mental Hygeine. <PERSON> Matz </PERSON> said repeated telephone calls and visits to <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s home by health officials failed to persuade her to get treatment for the disease she was diagnosed with last winter. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Comstock-Gay </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION>, said the state has the responsibility to protect the public. `` On the other hand, I do n't think state can force her to be treated. But they can keep her out of the public's way if she's going to be passing the disease frequently and easily,'' <PERSON> Comstock-Gay </PERSON> said `` If it were the cold or flu, it would be a different ballgame.'' Tuberculosis is an airborne bacteria that can be transmitted by sharing a close space with an infected person, <PERSON> Gursky </PERSON> said.
