<HEAD>Report More Money Needed for Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> may have to stop construction of a new satellite unless it can find about $ 200 million more to finish it, a newspaper reported Thursday. The satellite, designed as a communications vehicle and named for the biblical prophet <PERSON> Amos </PERSON>, is being built by government-run <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> and is scheduled for launch in 1993, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahronot </ORGANIZATION> said. Three other papers said some army generals opposed the project because of its high cost. Official declarations have said `` Amos'' would be used primarily for civilian purposes, beaming television, radio and telephone transmissions to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahronot </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> is expected to decide in a few weeks whether the job can be finished. An <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> official, speaking privately, confirmed the report but would not elaborate. The English-language Jerusalem Post Maj.-Gen. <PERSON> Ehud </PERSON> <PERSON> Barak </PERSON>, the deputy chief of staff, called the project as a `` Lavi fantasy. The Lavi was a U.S.-financed jet fighter project scrapped last year because of cost overruns. Other officers objected to the new satellite because it will cost at least $ 500 million, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> officials were reported to have said it would cost only half that. Other reports on the army controversy appeared in the socialist newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hamishmar </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday and <ORGANIZATION> Davar </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Davar </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials were leading the effort to obtain funds. Military and <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> spokesmen refused comment. Prof. <PERSON> Yuval </PERSON> <PERSON> Neeman </PERSON>, who heads <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s space agency, said in a telephone interview: `` <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials may have objected to the expenditure, but it is a commercial, not a military problem.'' He added, however: `` Government ministries, including the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, may have been asked to purchase broadcast channels on the satellite.'' News reports said the project was conceived by the private <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> headed by former army intelligence chief <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Amit </PERSON>. The debate over `` Amos'' comes two weeks after <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> launched its first space satellite, `` Horizon-1,'' which is said to carry surveillance equipment for possible intelligence gathering. <PERSON> Neeman </PERSON> said `` Horizon-1'' will stay in orbit through November, more than a month longer than originally scheduled. He said the flight would be extended because the craft was orbiting at a greater distance from Earth than planned.
