<HEAD>Justice To Stay Out Of Suit Against Northrop Over MX Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it will stay out of a private lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> which alleges the government was defrauded of more than $ 1 billion in connection with the manufacture of the MX missile-guidance system. The suit brought by eight current and former <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> employees accuses the company's electronics division of intentionally delivering to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> defective inertial measurement units, which guide the MX Peacekeeper missile. The 67-page complaint unsealed Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, and filed in October 1987, says <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> failed to ensure that the guidance components were properly manufactured, controlled, processed and inspected. It says <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> wrongfully received $ 1 billion from the government and seeks three times that amount. In addition, four of those filing the suit seek compensatory damages. The complaint was brought under the False Claims Act, which allows private parties to bring suit on behalf of the government and gives the government the right to join a case. Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has decided there is insufficient basis for it to enter the matter now. The government could enter the suit at a later time. In a related matter, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sued <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> in August 1987 for $ 3 million for failing to properly test a component of the MX. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> suit followed a private suit filed in 1986 by two of the eight <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> employees involved in the currently pending complaint. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman, said `` the quality and reliability of the inertial measurement units <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> builds has been measured consistently since the MX system became operational in December 1986, and has consistently met or bettered <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> expectations.''
