<FIRST>r a AM-InfantBurned     10-06 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infant Burned,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infant Dies in Hospital Flash Fire During Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An operating room flash fire fatally burned a 15-day-old premature baby undergoing emergency heart surgery Thursday, a hospital spokesman said. The 2-pound infant suffered second-degree burns over 60 percent of his body in the 8 a.m. fire. He died two hours later, said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` The baby was already in congestive heart failure and the burns combined to cause death,'' Wise said. Wise said the cause of the flash fire was n't known. `` Our technicians are looking at everything. The equipment was all working properly. It is very curious. We just do n't know,'' said Wise. None of the operating room surgeons or personnel was injured. Oxygen was being used during the procedure, <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> said, but added, `` There was nothing unique about this. No one has ever heard of this occurring.'' The infant, born 16 weeks premature, was suffering heart failure when the emergency procedure in the hospital's neonatal unit was started by a team of three surgeons, a neonatalologist, a nurse and an anesthesiologist. `` There were flames and the baby was lifted immediately up and taken to the intensive care unit. The baby was immediately put on life support, but died two hours later,'' said Wise. It was n't known if the parents were in the hospital at the time, said Wise, who did n't release the identity of the family or the name of the infant. `` The staff and nurses up there are devastated by this,'' Wise said. The surgery was meant to correct a congenital heart defect known as patent ductus arteriosus. The defect occurs when a small duct between the aorta, the artery leaving the left side of the heart, and the pulmonary artery, which leaves the right side of the heart, fails to close as it should soon after birth. As a result, blood from both sides is pumped into the pulmonary artery and from there into the lungs. `` Normally, medication is used, but 20 percent do n't respond,'' Wise said. `` They went in surgically to try to correct it. We've done this about 50 times earlier and there were no problems Nothing like this ever happened.'' Firefighters responded to an automatic alarmed triggered by activation of the sprinkler system, but the fire was out by the time they arrived, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, spokesman for the Fire Department. <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION>, located in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and other exclusive communities, is sometimes known as the `` hospital to the stars'' because of the many celebrities who are treated there.
