ry of the state,'' <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. The report examined Miss <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>'s behavior down to a microscopic level, including analyses of dog hairs found in feces, burn marks on Miss <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>'s jeans, and carpet fibers found in her former apartment. The report concluded Miss <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> spent much of her time during the four days at the apartment. The report said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> apparently burned a hole in her pants, scrawled `` nigger'' on her shoe, smeared dog feces on her body and clothing, and stepped into a plastic garbage bag in front of the apartment. The grand jury issued recommendations to the Legislature for legal reforms, including a proposal that would allow the relative of a dead person to bring a defamation case when the individual is falsely accused of a felony. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> and the grand jury also recommended enactment of an obstruction of justice law. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> has a law against obstruction of governmental administration, but it can not be used against <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> because it applies only when a threat of violence or a separate criminal act is employed, the attorney general said. He also called for changes in a state law that prevented him from moving against those who helped protect Mrs. <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> from arrest for contempt. Under state law, people can be charged with harboring a fugitive only if the offense for which the fugitive is wanted is a felony, <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. The contempt charge was not a felony.
