<HEAD>Humphrey The Wayward Whale Is Living Up to His Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SRO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BODEGA BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, the wayward humpback whale who wandered up the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> three years ago, was spotted Thursday feeding closer to shore than other migrating leviathans. `` We do n't think he's lost or sick, he could just be feeding on near shore fish,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Calambokidis </PERSON>, a research biologist for <ORGANIZATION> Cascadia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collective </ORGANIZATION>, which spotted the whale Saturday morning at <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>'s Bay. Fishermen also reported seeing what they believed to be the 40-foot humpback whale on Sunday and Tuesday. Coast Guard Chief Warrant Officer <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said their spotting was about 2.5 miles off <LOCATION> Bodega </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Head </LOCATION>, `` just lazying around.'' Cascadia's sighting marks the third consecutive year <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> has been sighted officially off the Sonoma-Marin coast since the fall of 1985, when he blundered into the tributary waters northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. For 25 days, the 45-ton whale wandered up and down the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delta </LOCATION>, gaining national publicity, poking into narrow sloughs and endangering his life because he was out of his salt-water habitat. The scientists, part of a private nonprofit group conducting a three-year study of humpback and blue whales, say they are sure they spotted <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>. They previously spotted him in 1986 and last year. Researcher <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Falxa </PERSON> said that among other things the whale was identified by multiple scarring on his dorsal fin. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> also is easily identifiable by the black and white color pattern and a lateral scar on his 15-foot fluke. The only thing unusual about <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>'s behavior is that he has been feeding well inshore from the other migrating whales congregating this time of the year near the <LOCATION> Farallon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> 26 miles off the mouth of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. The researchers are photographing and monitoring <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> for Cascadia and the Center for <ORGANIZATION> Whale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. The Cascadia researchers are studying the populations of blue and humpback whales and their migrations, and identifying individual animals like <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>. `` We have found record numbers of blue whales so far and about 100 to 200 humpbacks in the area each year,'' <PERSON> Calambokidis </PERSON> said. After <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> failed to find his way to freedom in 1985, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels eventually got the whale headed in the right direction and he cruised back into the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, cheered by hundreds of people.
