<DATELINE>NOVI SAD, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party bosses of <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> province were ousted Thursday night as a stone-throwing crowd of 30,000 people attacked their headquarters. The provincial leaders had promised to resign after a meeting with Serbian leaders earlier Thursday in the most dramatic development in three months of mass street protests over ethnic strife and an economic crisis. The development boosted a drive by <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s largest republic, for tighter control over its two autonomous provinces, <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> and ethnically troubled <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>. At least 41 people, including 14 policemen, were injured when the crowd outside the headquarters in this provincial capital of Novi Sad surged toward riot police guarding the building, hurling stones and breaking 20 windows. State-run news media said two policemen were seriously hurt and six people were hospitalized. Four people were reported arrested. The protesters, who held vigil outside the headquarters for two days, began to disperse after the leadership stepped down. Witnesses said police rebuffed an attempt by the crowds overnight Wednesday to force their way into the provincial <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> building. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, said the <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> party committee voted 87-10 to dismiss the 15-member Politburo, the highest political body in the province. Two members abstained in a meeting attended by 99 of the committee's 127 members. Provincial party leader <PERSON> Milovan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sogorov </PERSON> said a 10-member provisional group would be established while new leaders were chosen for <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION>, a flat, fertile area that produces most of the nation's grain. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said the provincial leadership promised to resign after meeting with Serbian party leaders in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, the nation's capital 40 miles to the south The agency quoted the Serbian party as saying: `` The <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> leadership has been deaf to the demands of the working class and other citizens. A serious split has occurred between the <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> leadership and the people.'' Outside the party headquarters in <LOCATION> Novo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sad </LOCATION>, protesters waved <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> flags and shouted complaints about low wages and declining living standards. Strikes and worker protests have become commonplace because of 217 percent annual inflation, 15 percent unemployment and austerity plans imposed because of a $ 21 billion foreign debt. Witnesses said demonstrators sang Serbian nationalist songs and chanted `` Police Go Away!'' `` We Are Going To Smash Windows!'' `` Thieves, Thieves!'' `` We Want Freedom!'' and `` We Are With You, <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON>!'' Tens of thousands of Serbs have rallied almost daily for three months in support of efforts by <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> party leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> to assert more authority in the provinces. Mass protests in Novi Sad started in response to the provincial party leadership's decision to discipline two members for supporting <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, Serbs, a largely <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> minority, claim harassment by ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s 2 million people and are predominantly Moslem. The southern province borders on <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. Gen. <PERSON> Nikola </PERSON> <PERSON> Ljubicic </PERSON>, a member of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s federal presidency and a former defense minister, told Serbian party leaders Thursday that `` eme