<HEAD>Soviet, U.S. Attorneys Battle American Businessman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with attorneys' arguments;
picks up 8th graf: `Gregorian's problems ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorneys for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government joined forces in federal appeals court Thursday, arguing that international relations will suffer if an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessman's lawsuit is upheld. `` We have been working very closely with the Soviets and we have made wonderful progress,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Letter </PERSON>. `` It's important that this progress not be set back.'' He was addressing a three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which is considering the case of <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>, an American denounced by the Soviets and barred from doing business in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> after 14 years. One of the judges, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinhard </PERSON>, bristled at the mention of foreign relations saying, `` Is n't that something we're supposed to ignore _ the political considerations _ in reaching our decision?'' <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> has sued the Soviets for libel. The Soviets have resisted and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has sided with the Soviets, saying they may not be sued for libel in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON>, ridiculed the contention that the case endangers U.S.-Soviet relations. `` I personally think they have bigger people to fry than my client,'' <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> told the court. `` I've never heard that we could n't conclude an arms agreement because of <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mage </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> attorney representing the Soviets, insisted that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts do not have jurisdiction because incidents involving <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> did not occur in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He also said the nation is immune from suit as a foreign sovereign. `` It's really two against one,'' <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> said of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet alignment in court. He has expressed bitterness over the government's abandonment of one of its own citizens in the legal proceedings. `` I look at this as a contest of politics versus justice,'' said <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON>. `` There's never been a case exactly like this before.'' <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>'s problems began in 1984 when, after a 14-year amicable relationship, the Soviets suddenly revoked <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>'s permit to sell medical supplies in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> Until then, his <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, had done a thriving business exporting such items as kidney dialysis machines, heart-lung machines and batteries for heart pacemakers. Soon after revoking his permit, the Soviets, through the official newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, printed a story denouncing <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> as a `` duplicitous negotiatior,'' accusing him of bribery and smuggling and intimating he was a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spy. <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>, adamant about his innocence, took an unprecedented action, suing the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for libel in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts. He also demanded that the Soviets pay for medical equipment still in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The Soviet defendants at first ignored the suit. But in 1985, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> entered a default judgment against them in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, awarding Gregorian total damages of $ 413,000. Of that amount, $ 250,000 was for libel. The Soviets refused to pay. <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> said he would seize Soviet assets, and to dramatize his claim, he took custody of a typewriter at an <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> correspondent's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, home as partial payment. Then, Soviet and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers went to court. The Soviet agency V.O. Medexport, which did business with Gregorian, asserted its immunity from suit under the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act and moved to reverse the judgment. On April 5, 1987, <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> dismissed his own libel judgment, ruling that he did not have jurisdiction because of immunity considerations. However, he let stand his ruling the Soviets should meet their contractual obligation to pay for the medical supplies. <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> appealed the ruling on libel to the 9th Circuit. The Soviets appealed the contractual award, as well as disputing the libel claim. <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON>'s argument is based on a theory that libel in connection with a commercial activity is exempt from immunities act and must be tried as a civil claim in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Popper </PERSON>, who represents the Soviets, said in his legal brief that there is no precedent for such a claim. `` Plaintiffs fail to cite a decision of any court in the entire world -LRB- including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -RRB- that has asserted jurisdiction on a claim of libel against a foreign sovereign,'' <PERSON> Popper </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s brief sided with the Soviets, saying `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not intend that foreign states could be sued for claims of libel.'' An additional view on the case has come from the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a public interest law and policy center which filed a friend of the court brief for Gregorian. `` WLF believes that the outrageous nature of the lies published by defendants-appellants is such that they should be held accountable,'' the foundation's lawyers argued. A ruling for the Soviets, they said, would reduce the ability of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts to protect the rights of citizens doing business overseas.
