<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Drinking,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets To Produce More Wine, Beer, Cognac In 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a major change for President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s anti-drinking campaign, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is planning to increase production of beer, wine, cognac and champagne by up to 38 percent to meet popular demand, a newspaper reported Thursday. However, the Trud labor daily said the government crusade has gone so far it will be difficult to significantly increase alcohol production soon. The drive was launched two months after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took power as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief in March 1985. `` We have to restore a significant part of production, and that's complicated,'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Konobov </PERSON>, deputy chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s food division, told the newspaper. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in 1985 ordered a reduction in the production of vodka and other alcoholic beverages, an increase in their price, an increase in the minimum drinking age to 21 and cuts in the hours and numbers of stores that could sell alcohol. He has since cited the campaign as a major reason in the increased life expectancy for Soviet men. But the anti-drinking drive has provoked nationwide grumbling, and even indignation, because Soviets now must stand in long lines just to buy an occassional bottle of wine or beer. Cuts in government alcohol production also have proved a bonanza for the country's moonshiners. Sugar now must be rationed in many cities because of shortages caused by the thousands of Soviets who use it to produce `` samogon,'' or home brew. <PERSON> Konobov </PERSON> said the goal set by the 1985 anti-drinking drive was `` noble,'' but that it has been pursued by bureaucratic means. `` So it is obvious that corrections are necessary,'' he said. According to Trud, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> has proposed for next year to increase wine production by 38 percent, to 675 million gallons; beer, by 12 percent, to 1.8 billion gallons; cognac, by 28 percent, to 33.2 million gallons, and champagne, by 9 percent, to 58 million gallons. The newspaper said vodka and other strong drinks would continue to be manufactured in quantities laid down by a government decree in 1985. Plans also call for more spirits to be imported from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, one of the world's biggest rum producers, and from <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and other countries, <PERSON> Konobov </PERSON> said. According to figures released by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency, there are more than 4.5 million officially registered alcoholics in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and the total number is believed to be much more. As one of the new methods being tried to discourage alcohol abuse, Soviet television on Tuesday night broadcast a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television movie titled `` Life of the Party,'' starring <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, which told the true-life story of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> woman who joined Alcoholics Anonymous to beat the bottle.
