<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     10-06 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Says New Law Gives Ortega Dictatorial Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition leaders said Thursday a new emergency law gives President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> dictatorial powers and is likely to be applied soon. The law, approved Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, gives the president authority to declare a state of emergency and restrict civil rights for reasons of war, economic crisis or national disaster. It took effect immediately. U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, have been fighting to overthrow the leftist government since 1981 and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is in an economic crisis. The opposition in the 96-seat assembly said in a statement that the law bestows on <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> `` too great a concentration of extraordinary powers,'' making him an `` absolute dictator.'' <PERSON> Erick </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` The new law consolidates the dictatorial and totalitarian state, and just as in the <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> of -LRB- President Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the Nicaraguan people should say ` No' to the Sandinistas.'' Chileans voted Wednesday against letting <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> extend his 15-year rule. <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> complained that the law `` legalizes repression against the internal opposition to consolidate the power of the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> and gives the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> arguments for pushing military aid for the Contras.'' Both <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurdian </PERSON>, acting president of the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinate </ORGANIZATION>, the country's main opposition group, said the government could be expected to apply the law soon. An emergency decree was in effect in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> most of the time from March 1982 until shortly after a regional peace plan was signed by the five Central American presidents in August 1987. The decree's provisions included press censorship, suspension of some civil rights, and searches without warrants. The new law goes further. It allows the president to close news media and theaters; intervene in mail or electronic correspondence; take over private vehicles and businesses; make preventive arrests, and prevent individuals from entering or leaving the country. It gives the president authority to expand or reduce his own authority to take the steps and to continue the measures until the reasons for them disappear. The law says certain basic rights can not be suspended. They include the rights to life, equality, freedom of conscience, asylum, thought and religion, to be presumed innocent until proven guilty, to have personal property, and to be free from slavery in prison. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday also approved legislation banning the receipt of any type of assistance approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and destined for opposition groups, the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> church, labor unions and individuals. Under the law, any person found to have accepted <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance could face between four and 12 years imprisonment. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed a new $ 27 million, six-month, non-military aid package for the Contras Oct. 1. On Tuesday, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to set up an international peace force to take Contras and leftist Salvadoran rebels from its territory. It said the rebels should be taken first to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, then resettled elsewhere. Thursday in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, Assistant Foreign Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> rejected that proposal. <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> told reporters relocating the Contras in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> would violate that country's principles of neutrality. The only way the proposal could be considered would be for the rebels to abandon the war and become refugees or political exiles, <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> said. A rebel leader said Thursday that some Contras in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> were returning to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> that `` our troops are returning to their original positions'' inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The report could not be immediately confirmed. A rebel spokesman in <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>, the Honduran capital, acknowledged some Contra forces had returned to Nicaraguan border provinces but declined to provide details. The official spoke on condition of anonymity. Contras have used base camps on the Honduran side of the border since they began fighting in 1981 to overthrow the Sandinista government.
