<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> leads <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> 47 percent to 41 percent in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, according to a poll released Thursday, but the gap between the two candidates was closed by a nearly six-point margin of error. The poll, conducted for <ORGANIZATION> KING </ORGANIZATION> 5 News by <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, says <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> leads <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in all geographic regions of the state, including <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, where the margin is 48 percent to 41 percent. Between Sept. 30 and Oct. 2, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> polled 300 likely voters in the Nov. 8 election. The margin of error was plus or minus 5.8 percent.
