<HEAD>African Leader Calls for Conference On African Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with toasts.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The recently elected chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> called for an international conference on African debt during a meeting with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Thursday, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of state for African Affairs, said <PERSON> Moussa </PERSON> <PERSON> Traore </PERSON>, the president of <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>, told <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that he `` wants to avoid a confrontation between debtors and creditors.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> referred enquiries about the details of <PERSON> Traore </PERSON>'s proposal to officials of <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>. At the Embassy of <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>, an aide said all of the officials familiar with the proposal were with <PERSON> Traore </PERSON> and could not be reached. `` His party would have to speak primarily for him, but he would like to see an international conference on African debt and made that known during the meeting,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` He wants to avoid a confrontation between debtors and creditors and that's why he was stressing this global approach.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials at the meeting `` discussed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approach in terms of dealing with individual cases, case by case, and our interest in trying to encourage those who are serious about reforming their economy and not necessarily rewarding the worst performers.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> expressed concern that <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, which has been involved in war with <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>, is developing the capacity to produce chemical weapons. He said the president emphasized `` the need for all of us to be vigilant in that regard.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has previously expressed concern that <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> has a plant that may be approaching capability to produce such weapons. `` We have an interest therefore in an international approach to take mesures against the use of such weapons,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. The president proposed an international conference on the subject during his speech to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> last week. In remarks at a welcoming ceremony on the South Lawn of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> praised <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>'s economic reform program, which has made the impoverished <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> nation a major African recipient of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic aid. Since becoming chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION> at the African summit in May, he told <PERSON> Traore </PERSON>, `` You have already demonstrated your interest in helping to promote regional settlements in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>.'' `` We hope the <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION> can play an even more active role in solving those regional problems and play a key role in promoting development in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> by encouraging economic reform and cooperation,'' he said. <PERSON> Traore </PERSON>, in his response, said he was `` convinced ... that our discussions will enable us to make progress in the search for a solution to the problems which are of concern to both our sides.'' As he posed for photographs with <PERSON> Traore </PERSON> before their closed meeting, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> responded to a question about human rights in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> by saying, `` I think we are sitting beside a man in whose country that is a major goal.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the two leaders met privately for half an hour and then met in a larger group for an additional half hour. At a state dinner for <PERSON> Traore </PERSON> on Thursday night, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he was `` gratified that you share our concern about regional stability and economic development in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'' and added that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would `` continue to work with you and be as supportive as we can in these areas.'' Responding to the president's toast, <PERSON> Traore </PERSON>, speaking in French, said through an interpreter that the <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION> would continue to seek `` the taking down of the intolerable system of apartheid'' in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. He said also that it was `` urgent to find a just and lasting solution to the problem of the African debt.''
