<HEAD>Company, Executives Indicted in Postal Service Contract Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf to CLARIFY; SUBS 21st graf pvs bgng, `Casey,
who,' to reflect that Casey only held postmaster general job for
seven months. ADDS 1 graf to end to show subsequent postmasters
general</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> company and two of its executives were accused Thursday of participating with a <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> governor in a contract bid-rigging scheme that included replacing the postmaster general. The replacement of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlin </PERSON> with <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> as postmaster general was engineered in 1986 as part of the elaborate effort by <ORGANIZATION> Recognition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to get $ 400 million worth of contracts to provide automated mail-sorting equipment, according an indictment returned here. The indictment charged that the company; REI's chairman, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON>, a vice president, conspired with <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, then vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> board of governors, and others to manipulate bid procedures, obtain confidential information about competitors and replace <PERSON> Carlin </PERSON>, considered an obstacle to REI winning contracts. An unindicted co-conspirator, <PERSON> Voss </PERSON> received $ 19,000 in kickbacks plus $ 4,000 worth of airline tickets from a Detroit-area public relations firm headed by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gnau </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> that REI hired on <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>' recommendation, the indictment said <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, who received a four-year sentence for his 1986 guilty plea in the case, also was promised one-quarter of one percent of any revenues REI earned from <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> contracts, it said. The indictment charged that through <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, REI arranged for the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 to halt procurement of a multiline optical character reader system and set up a two-step test period to give it another chance to win the lucrative order. After the procurement scheme came to light in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ultimately decided to give the revised contract to <ORGANIZATION> ElectroCom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which had beat out REI for the earlier phase of the contract. But if REI had won the competition, it would have been positioned to obtain procurement contracts worth $ 4.6 billion over the next five years, said <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Loozen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, who headed President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1980 <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> presidential campaign, pleaded guilty to charges he took kickbacks totaling at least $ 30,000 on four <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> contracts and expense account fraud. <PERSON> Gnau </PERSON>, another unindicted co-conspirator who headed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1980 <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> campaign, received a three-year sentence for conspiracy and for paying an illegal $ 2,500 gratuity to <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gnau </PERSON> agreed to cooperate with the investigation along with another executive of his firm, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON>, who received a six-month sentence for paying illegal gratuities to <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Loozen </PERSON> said the bid rigging scandal delayed procurement of a new optical mail-scanner system for about 14 months. The system is now expected to be completely installed next May. In sentencing memos filed in the earlier cases, prosecutors estimated that the bid-rigging activities of <PERSON> Voss </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gnau </PERSON> cost the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> hundreds of millions of dollars the agency planned to save through automation. The indictment charged REI, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, 49, and <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON>, 46, both of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, with conspiracy to defraud the government, theft of <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> property, mail and wire fraud and aiding and abetting. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON> each face maximum possible prison terms of 33 years and fines of more than $ 1.5 million if convicted. The company could be fined more than $ 3 million if convicted. REI spokeswoman <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> said, `` Neither the company nor Mr. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> nor Mr. <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON> have done anything wrong. We do not believe the indictment should have been brought by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. attorney.'' `` The company, Mr. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and Mr. <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON> intend to defend this matter to the fullest extent. We are confident we will be exonerated,'' she said. In a statement, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said: `` Public corruption is one of democracy's worst enemies. This indictment represents our commitment to prosecute aggressively and vigorously those who seek to strike at the heart of fairness in the procurement process by corrupting the machinery of government for personal financial gain.'' According to the indictment, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spartin </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Gnau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, who also headed an executive placement firm, influenced the selection of a new postmaster by obtaining management consulting contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Spartin </PERSON>, also named an unindicted co-conspirator, used his position `` to insinuate himself into the confidence of high-level <ORGANIZATION> USPS </ORGANIZATION> and board officials'' but concealed his relationship to <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gnau </PERSON> and REI. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> _ who became postmaster general in January 1986 and served only seven months until early August 1986 _ was one of three candidates that <PERSON> Spartin </PERSON> recommended, through <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, as a replacement for <PERSON> Carlin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Spartin </PERSON>, who concealed from <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> his interest in REI's effort to get a mail-sorting contract, also was instrumental in the removal of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jellison </PERSON>, a deputy postmaster general who was also regarded as an obstacle, the indictment charged. <PERSON> Spartin </PERSON> is also cooperating with authorities in the investigation, according to sources who spoke on condition of anonymity. The procurement scheme began to unravel when some postal inspectors aboard a commercial airline noticed <PERSON> Voss </PERSON> traveling in coach, even though postal governors were allowed to fly first class, sources said. Tracing his expense account vouchers, inspectors discovered that <PERSON> Voss </PERSON> had collected reimbursement for $ 70,000 worth of first-class air travel when he spent only $ 26,000 on coach seats, a prosecutor said when <PERSON> Voss </PERSON> pleaded guilty to embezzlement. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> was succeeded as postmaster general in August 1986 by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON>. He held the job until <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> banker, took over last March 1.
