<HEAD>Envoy Says ``Modest Progress'' Made In Peace Talks With Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s foreign minister said Thursday progress was made in recent Iran-Iraq peace talks, but he still accused <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> of balking on some issues and declined to comment on whether a compromise was near. `` The <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> delegation entered into substantive talks and modest progress has been made,'' said <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> after separate meetings in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> side and with Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>. `` I can not go into details, but I can tell you the situation is better now than in the beginning,'' he told a news conference. Asked about the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hostages held by pro-Iranian extremists in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, he said, `` I categorically deny there are any talks between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and no talks on the hostage issue.'' <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> said he was willing to resume talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s representative and with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> on Oct. 26 or Oct 27, if requested by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> agreed to only one negotiating session in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> renewed peace talks Saturday at <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after a session in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> from Aug. 25 to Sept. 13. The talks followed a cease-fire Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old war, which left at least 1 million killed or wounded. <PERSON> Velyati </PERSON> emphasized he was not fully satisfied with the outcome of meetings with <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> and blamed <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for introducing what he called extraneous issues. `` I am not altogether pleased or greatly encouraged in the pace of the talks,'' <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> said. He added that both sides have not yet `` been able to achieve the goals that the secretary-general had set.'' These goals are formalization of the cease-fire, withdrawal by both sides to international boundaries and repatriation of prisoners of war, under terms of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Security Council Resolution 598. <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> avoided a direct answer when asked if a compomise deal had been struck, in which <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would halt searching neutral shipping in the gulf, as reported by <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> sources. In turn, the sources said, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> would postpone discussion of sovereignty over the disputed <PERSON> Shatt </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Arab </PERSON> waterway between the two nations. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> sources have reported that such a deal, arranged by the secretary-general, was virtually in place and could break the deadlock between the two sides over clearing of the <PERSON> Shatt </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Arab </PERSON>, sovereignty over the channel and other issues. <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> did not deny a deal in the future but emphasized that for the time being <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would not give up its right to search suspect ships in time of war.
