<HEAD>Myerson Case: What the Law Clerk Heard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While a state judge was ruling favorably in the divorce case of <PERSON> Bess </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>'s lover, the former Miss <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was calling the judge on an unlisted, private line, the judge's former law clerk testified Thursday. Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> called more than a dozen times and gave an assumed name to court personnel, the law clerk also testified at the divorce-fixing trial of the two women and <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>'s lover, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> `` Andy'' <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON> case was one of the few handled personally by the judge, law clerk <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON> testified. Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON> and state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Hortense </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> each face five counts of conspiracy, mail fraud and bribe-related charges in an alleged 1983 scheme to slash <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>'s child support and alimony payments In his second day of federal court testimony, <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON> said that of more than 3,000 requests to change alimony and child support payments, the <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON> case was one of the few Mrs. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> handled personally. `` I think I'll do this one myself, <PERSON> Howie </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON> said the judge told him in July 1983 after <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>'s lawyer sought to delay weekly alimony and child support payments of $ 1,850 a week to <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>. Asked if Mrs. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> had given similar personal attention to other support requests, <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON>, who was her law secretary from 1981 until her resignation last year, said: `` Maybe one or two.'' Prosecutors charge that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>, the city's former cultural affairs commissioner, gave a $ 19,000 city job to Mrs. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON>'s unemployed daughter, <PERSON> Sukhreet </PERSON>, in order to influence the outcome of the judge's decision <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON>, the prosecution's second witness, testified that in the summer of 1983, Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> began calling the judge on a private, unlisted phone. Prosecutors contend that even though Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> knew each other, their contacts were limited until the judge began handling interim decisions in the <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON> divorce. <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> often called identifying herself either as `` <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> or <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON> said he did n't recognize the voice although the woman called `` a fairly large number -LRB- of times -RRB- between a dozen and two dozen.'' The clerk said he asked Mrs. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> `` who is this <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> person?'' He said the judge replied: `` Oh, that's <PERSON> Bess </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> She's just being so Byzantine.'' On Sept. 14, 1983, about a month after <PERSON> Sukhreet </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> was made a special assistant to <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>, the judge cut <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>'s temporary alimony and child support payments from $ 1,850 to $ 680 a week When an Oct. 18, 1983 <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> story reported the `` coincidence'' of Ms. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON>'s hiring by the <ORGANIZATION> Cultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> asked <P