<HEAD>Teacher Confronted Gunmen, Witnesses Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 10-year-old boy and a Christian school's headmaster testified Thursday that a woman who teaches third grade came to the defense of her youngsters by attacking a gunman with a book. `` This is a .357 Magnum,'' headmaster <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carden </PERSON> quoted defendant <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> as telling teacher <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanton </PERSON>. `` I do n't care what it is _ get out of here,'' <PERSON> Carden </PERSON> quoted her as replying. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> is charged with kidnapping 110 people at the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> End </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> on Feb. 2. Defending himself in state court here as a crusader for people's constitutional rights, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> has called Mrs. <PERSON> Blanton </PERSON> `` a fiesty lady.'' Ten-year-old <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Vice </PERSON> said he saw Mrs. <PERSON> Blanton </PERSON> encounter <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> and another gunman in a hallway, where she began hitting <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> with a book. The other man, described by police as an unwilling accomplice, testified Thursday he was duped by <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> into helping take over the school and later was threatened with his life if he tried to back out. <PERSON> Marty </PERSON>, then a fourth-grader, said he was coming out of the bathroom when he saw two men walk in at the other end of the hallway. After seeing the confrontation with Mrs. <PERSON> Blanton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> said, he ducked into the nearest classroom. Asked why he did not return to his own class, <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> said, `` I did n't want them to get me.'' <PERSON> Carden </PERSON> told the jury that when he heard of the trouble, he and a coach rushed to the elementary school building and saw Mrs. <PERSON> Blanton </PERSON> struggling with <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, while he held a cocked pistol pointed toward the ceiling. <PERSON> Carden </PERSON> said he and the coach then told Mrs. <PERSON> Blanton </PERSON> to do whatever <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> told her to do. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 43, testified that he was picking up beer cans near an unemployment office that day when <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> offered him $ 50 to help him move across town. Instead, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> drove him to the school, gave him an empty gun and told him to put it in his coat pocket. `` He said this was something he had been planning for two or three years,'' <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> said. `` What he planned I did n't know.'' <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> told the jury that when he and <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> entered the school, he told <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> he wanted to leave. `` You ai n't no more your own boss,'' he quoted <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> as saying. `` You do it or die.'' The two men entered the school at 8:30 a.m. and about 2:30 p.m., <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> said he surrendered to an officer who offered him more money than <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> promised. `` He asked me if $ 300 would do me any good. I said yes. I gave him the gun and I walked out. I was wanting to go anyway.'' Kidnapping charges against <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> were dropped after authorities decided he was an unwilling participant. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> surrendered after 12 hours when authorities produced a videotape in which Gov. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, who is to testify Friday at <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s insistence, offered a bogus pardon. Cross-examining six <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> policemen who identified weapons taken from the school, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> suggested the guns showed he `` was very serious about what he believed.'' `` I had a right to act as a steward for those children and their future ... against pollution, deceit and people who are destroying the Constitution of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> said while questioning one officer.
</TEXT>
