<HEAD>Namibia-Angola Talks Set For Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will meet Friday to discuss the implementation of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s independence, and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s withdrawal of its soldiers from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> confirmed The exact time and location for the talks were not determined and it was not yet confirmed whether the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would continue mediating the talks, as it has in previous meetings, said <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION>, on Thursday. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has told Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> it is ready to begin implementation on Nov. 1 of <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Resolution 435 to give neighboring <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, its freedom. Resolution 435, passed a decade ago, is a one-year plan for national assembly elections under <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> supervision. About 7,500 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping troops and 2,000 civilian support staff are to be sent to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> in an operation estimated to cost between $ 600 million and $ 700 million. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled the former German colony since World War I. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> revoked a mandate from its predecessor, the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, and declared <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>'s rule over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> illegal. Complicating the plan is <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s insistence that about 50,000 Cuban troops stationed in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to protect that country's Marxist government from the <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> rebel movement should be withdrawn in a year <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> stands for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The Cubans have reportedly compromised their initial insistence on a four-year withdrawal down to two years, with a phased withdrawal away from southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s border with northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. Officials involved in the talks among the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, have expressed confidence that a mutually acceptable compromise will be reached on the withdrawal timetable.
</TEXT>
