<HEAD>Science Policy Maker Resigns Federal Position During Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> official who helped set <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Administration policies regulating biology research said Thursday he is resigning to resume research, not because the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is investigating him for possible financial conflicts of interest. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> for biological, behavioral and social sciences for the last four years, said he is resigning because `` I want to go back to the laboratory.'' He confirmed that a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation of his financial interests is continuing, but said, `` That's not why I've resigned. <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON> formally leaves the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 15, and assumes a new position as a full professor at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> on Nov. 1. He said the university job will include continuation of a research project that has been under way for several years and `` now is at a critical point.'' In his letter of resignation, dated Sept. 23, <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON> said he was making the move to return to research and because of `` the stress on both the agency and me over the past year resulting from publicity about my activities outside <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION>.'' He acknowledged that he has been accused of having improper connections with biotechnology companies that could have been affected by <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> policies, but denied that there is a conflict. <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON> said that shortly after his appointment to the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, he submitted a list of his holdings to the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> general counsel. He said the counsel advised him to sell only one investment, stock in the <ORGANIZATION> Chiron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Emeryville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a biotechnology company. The other holdings were not considered to be a conflict of interest, he said. Some companies in which he holds stock have been incorrectly identified as biotechnology companies, said <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON>, saying, `` Whether or not they are biotechnology companies is a matter of interpretation.'' He identified one of his holdings as <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION>, a company that he said makes laboratory equipment, but does no biotechnology research. <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON> said he has hired an attorney to assist him in the continuing <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> probe, but that the investigation started more than a year ago and nothing has come of it. `` I have not been charged with any conflict of interest,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> announced <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON>'s resignation last week in a two-paragraph statement from <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> director. In the statement, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> would not comment on an investigation of <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON>, but did note that `` concerns have arisen and have been under consideration by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> concerning certain of Dr. <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON>'s financial and business relationships, especially with regard to financial disclosure.'' <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON> is a former <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> researcher and a specialist in the genetics of brain ailments, such as Alzheimer's disease. At the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION>, he has been a major influence on policies regulating the biotechnology industry during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. Experts representing the Environmental Defense Fund have charged that <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON> helped formulate regulations that favored the biotechnology industry and genetic experiments. `` <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON>'s past history has been pro-industry,'' said <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldburg </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> EDF </ORGANIZATION> scientist. She said <PERSON> Kingsbury </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration were ineffective in setting policies regulating experiments using organisms that have been altered genetically in the laboratory.
