<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday AMs, Oct. 13, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Two New Books Praise and Assail Indonesia's Co-Founder Sukarno</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The President <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> who died in disgrace 18 years ago is again stirring controversy in the nation he led to independence from the Dutch after World War II. Two recently published books spotlight the leader whose vivid personality has an almost mythic hold on many Indonesians who refer to themselves as Sukarnoists. In the memoirs of Col. <PERSON> Bambang </PERSON> <PERSON> Widjanarko </PERSON>, his military aide from 1960 to 1968, <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> is portrayed as helplessly buffeted by political forces beyond his control during an aborted communist coup Sept. 30, 1965. Some critics complained that <PERSON> Bambang </PERSON>'s `` Eight Years Near Sukarno'' glosses over <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON>'s shortcomings, but it is the less controversial of the two books. The other book, in the view of Sukarnoists, should be banned for blackening the reputation of the nation's co-founder. It is titled `` He Who Sows The Wind Will Reap The Storm'' and says <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> was involved in the aborted coup and was a committed Marxist since his student days in the 1920s. Written by <PERSON> Sugiarso </PERSON> <PERSON> Surojo </PERSON>, a former intelligence officer who now edits a women's magazine, `` He Who Sows'' describes <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> as `` a conspirator adept at concealing his true identity.'' Charges of complicity in the uprising in which six top army generals were slain are not new. Several military tribunals heard testimony years ago that <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> knew the coup was planned but did nothing to prevent it. Earlier foes also denounced what they saw as his demogoguery, hedonistic lifestyle and tilt toward the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which is now banned. <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> remained as president in name only after signing over power on March 11, 1966, to Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON>, who foiled the revolt five months earlier. <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON>, who is now 66, are the only presidents this country has known. <PERSON> Sugiarso </PERSON> said he was inspired to write his book partly by the revival of Sukarnoism during last year's general election campaign. Thousands of young Indonesians in red T-shirts and headbands thronged rallies in support of the <ORGANIZATION> Indonesian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, a grouping of five political parties, one of which was founded by <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> 61 years ago. The party had been faring poorly and its leaders calculated correctly that the <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> magnetism would help revive its fortunes. With <PERSON> Megawati </PERSON> <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON>'s daughters, among the successful candidates last year, the party increased its representation in the 500-seat <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> from 24 to 40 members and its proportion of the total vote from 7.9 to 11 percent. With Sukarnoism making a comeback among youth, <PERSON> Sugiarso </PERSON> said, his book is intended to balance what he called a lopsided view of history fostered by the country's founding generation. `` The time has come for our national history to be straightened, written objectively, so as to be a mirror for our future leaders and for the young generation who have not known their true national history,'' he said. Attorney General <PERSON> Sukarton </PERSON> <PERSON> Marmosudjono </PERSON> described the book as unethical but rejected calls to ban it. Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Rudini </PERSON> also objected to the book and Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Harsudiono </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartas </PERSON>, chief of the armed forces social and political section, urged a stop to the <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> `` polemic.'' No sales figures were available but booksellers said it was moving briskly. <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> was officially forgotten and rarely mentioned favorably in ruling circles after his death at the age of 69 from a kidney ailment June 21, 1970. Once hailed for his vision of a unified nation free of Dutch colonial rule, his economic policies had virtually bankrupted <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. Popular interest in <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> was reignited after the government decided in 1979 to build an elaborate tomb for his remains, replacing a simple grave that was covered by a faded yellow parasol. Newspapers were allowed for the first time in years to mention his name. Portraits of <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> went on sale and a two-week exhibit of memorabilia attracted throngs. Books he wrote books came off the banned list. Statues of <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> and the country's first vice president and co-founder, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatta </PERSON>, were dedicated in 1980 at the site where they declared independence on Aug. 17, 1945. <PERSON> Hatta </PERSON> resigned in 1956, partly as a result of disenchantment with <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON>'s leadership, and died in 1980 <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>'s efficient new airport was renamed the SukarnoHatta International Airport three years ago. The son of a schoolteacher and a Balinese dancer, <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> became one of the best known nationalists in what then was the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indies </LOCATION> after forming a political party in 1927. The Dutch sentenced him to four years in prison in 1929. Freed in 1931, he was arrested again the following year and spent the next eight years in exile in the outer islands. His exile ended when the Japanese invaded during World War II and freed him. Some Indonesians accused him of collaborating with the Japanese. Following their declaration of independence in 1945, <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hatta </PERSON> raised an army and and took to the jungle for a four-year struggle against the Dutch. Although the Dutch captured and again exiled <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> in 1948, his battle for independence stirred world opinion, and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> urged freedom for the nation. <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> was freed in 1949 and later that year the Dutch relinquished power.
</TEXT>
