<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm ADV09   10-06 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, ADV 09,0839</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Like Ball Players, Farmers Looking to Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some people are betting that the devastating drought of 1988 is over, that next year will see a return to normalcy in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crop production. After all, they say, that's been the historical pattern. There were helpful rains the last couple of months, and the crop growing season has virtually ended. So there is less news about the drought, although in huge areas of the nation dryness still prevails, the deep, subsoil kind that will require a foot or two of precipitation to remedy. All in all, say <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> economists, most farmers and ranchers have survived the crop and pasture losses better than some thought possible at midyear when heat and drought were so rampant. One important note of optimism came recently from the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Drought temporarily slowed the recovery in farmland values, but appraisers think land prices will climb at a healthy clip in 1989. `` Land prices primarily reflect long-term expectations for farm income, interest rates and other factors,'' says agency economist <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hexem </PERSON>. `` But short-term events such as the drought can reduce farmers' liquidity, which in turn reduces the demand for farmland or increases supply of land on the market if farms fail.'' A survey of rural appraisers in August indicated that farmland prices nationwide rose 1.2 percent from May 1 to the end of July, slightly behind the 1.8 percent increase for the preceding three months. Looking to this fall, the appraisers said they expected land values to rise an average of only 0.9 percent from Aug. 1 through October. But they also indicated farmland values may rise 4.6 percent in 1989, faster than a 3.6 percent increase forecast last May prior to the main drought impact. `` If the inflation rate continues to edge upward, farmland values may improve,'' <PERSON> Hexem </PERSON> said. `` However, wariness about next year's growing conditions, farm incomes and interest rates seem to be dampening the near-term outlook, particularly in areas where the drought has been most severe.'' By reducing grain output, driving up commodity prices and putting livestock producers in a bind for forage and emergency feed supplies, the drought took a further toll of producers who had suffered the financial crunch of earlier years. `` There likely wo n't be as many farms next year as there would have been without the 1988 drought,'' says another agency economist, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, in the October issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine. Drought, he said, created financial hardships that `` have accelerated many of the forces that were already leading to fewer but larger farms'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. This consolidation, or decline in farm numbers, occurred rapidly _ averaging almost 3 percent a year _ after the peak in 1935 of 6.81 million farms. Then, in the early 1970s, exploding export markets made farming financially attractive. According to the 1982 census of agriculture, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said, the number of farms in the preceding decade declined only 0.4 percent a year. In the early 1980s, as lower commodity prices and rising interest rates squeezed producers, profits from farmland dropped and so did land values. Farm numbers declined again and consolidations increased. `` Farmers hurt most by the drought are offering land for sale or rent in sufficient numbers to slow the rise in land values that began last year, following six years of decline,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. `` This lowers the price of land relative to its value, leading to further consolidations by farmers with growth potential.'' But the drought is causing consolidation differently according to region. In winter wheat areas of the southern <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, yields were high this year, and with rising market prices `` the consolidation would be somewhat like that experienced in boom times, including a slowing in the rate of exit'' from farming, he said. `` But for farmers growing spring wheat in the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, production was down by half, incomes were cut, and the consolidation would be more like that experienced during bust times,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. Urbanization, conversion to non-farm uses, rising transportation costs, and expenses associated with new technologies are some other factors that affect farmland consolidation. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said a number of factors are working against the tendency to farm consolidation, including: _ Selling off parcels of land for city growth can result in a larger number of small farms _ Non-farm incomes help ensure survival of smaller farm operations, including part-time and hobby farms _ Some farms that produce specialty commodities appear small by some measures but are proving profitable and durable _ Larger farms sometimes reach a size beyond which they can grow no more and may even break up into smaller farms Census information shows that large farms `` are just as likely to break into small ones as small farms are to blossom into large ones.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Oct. 9</NOTE>
