<HEAD>Oil Prices Tumble, Stocks Post Small Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil prices have slipped further to new two year lows, and takeover speculation has helped the stock market post a modest gain. Congressional investigators, meanwhile, report finding no widespread price gouging at grocery stores in the wake of the summer drought. In the oil futures market, reports of growing supplies and speculation about friction among key producers were cited for sending crude oil prices below $ 13 a barrel Wednesday. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> dropped 47 cents to settle at $ 12.60 a barrel. The benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude traded as low as a $ 12.28 barrel during a hectic session. Over the past month, the near-term crude oil contract price has fallen $ 2.19 a barrel to the lowest level since August 1986. Prices for refined products traded on the exchange, such as wholesale unleaded gasoline and home heating oil, also fell. Among the rumors sparking fears in the market was talk that <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> had decided to leave the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, and that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, considered a stabilizing force, would step down. Both rumors were denied, analysts said. Also contributing to the decline was an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report, released after the close of trading Tuesday, that showed a higher-than-expected increase in crude oil stocks and a sharp increase in refinery production. Stock prices were supported by takeover speculation, analysts said. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.45 points to 2,106.51 on Wednesday, while advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, a report from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said pasta, cereal and white bread prices rose more between June and August than they did in the same period last year. But <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committeee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., said, `` in general, there do not seem to have been excessive price increases across a broad range of products that use the drought as an excuse. In other economic news: _ More than two-thirds of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> surveyed want to see the rich pay more taxes, while an increasing number of people are growing disenchanted with the new tax law, according to a Money magazine survey on Americans and their money _ The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, said his agency can no longer cover the cost of rescuing ailing savings institutions without placing `` an exceedingly heavy burden'' on the industry He told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> it will cost $ 45 billion to $ 50 billion to clean up the industry, boosting an earlier projection by more than one-third.
