<HEAD>Irving Chairman Agrees To A Friendly Bank of NY Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s longest and most bitterly contested takeover battles is nearing an end, with <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s top management accepting a sweetened $ 1.4 billion offer from rival <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The announcement Wednesday came one day after <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> lost a key court battle on its anti-takeover `` poison pill'' defense. Irving Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said he would recommend the board of directors approve the merger and drop all pending lawsuits and anti-takeover defenses used to ward off <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s year-long advances He also promised to move up his retirement plans and leave after the deal was completed. A special board meeting was set for Friday, although many banking experts have called the vote a formality. `` We're 99 percent there. I believe the board will go along with <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Adair </PERSON>, a banking analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Under the revised bid, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> would pay $ 15 in cash and 1.675 shares of its own stock for each of Irving's 18.9 million common shares outstanding. It also included warrants valued at $ 5 a share toward the purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> stock. The entire deal would be worth about $ 76 a share, or around $ 1.4 billion, about $ 200 million higher than the hostile offer. The previous bid had the same amount of cash but slightly less stock and did not include the warrants. Irving shares jumped $ 3.75 to close at $ 73.50 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, while <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> fell 75 cents to $ 34.12 -LCB-. Neither side would comment on the turn of events leading to the tentative pact. But banking analysts agreed <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> was forced to negotiate with its unwanted suitor after losing Tuesday's court rulings and in the absence of any friendly `` white knight'' takeover partner. The appellate division of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday struck down a key provision of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s `` poison pill'' anti-takeover defense. The defense would have allowed all <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> shareholders except a hostile suitor to buy $ 400 worth of Irving shares for $ 200 if any suitor bought more than 20 percent of Irving stock without the support of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s management. The plan was intended to make a hostile takeover bids prohibitively expensive. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> had vowed to appeal the ruling to the state's <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, but some legal experts questioned whether that court would have considered the case since the appellate division's decision was unanimous. `` The court ruling closed down one of their last possible escape routes,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` They had very few options left.'' Last spring, Milan-based <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerciale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Italiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, offered to merge with <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> as part of a major restructuring of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bank. But it recently withdrew its bid after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> ruled the Italian government agency that owned most of <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerciale </ORGANIZATION> had to supply separate financial imformation. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> already has given conditional approval for an Irving-Bank of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> merger. A merger would nearly double <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s size, vaulting it close to the top 10 of the nation's largest banking companies. The two had a combined $ 47.8 billion in assets as of June 30. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 4.9 percent of Irving, had maintained since unveiling its takeover proposal on Sept. 25, 1987, that a merger would be a good fit because both banks have similar markets and services. While many analysts agreed, they also speculated <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yor