<HEAD>Japan Provides $7.45 Billion In Development Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> provided a record $ 7.45 billion in development assistance in 1987, up 32.3 percent from a year earlier, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The ministry said in an annual report that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was the second largest foreign aid donor in 1987 after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which extended $ 8.77 billion in assistance. But <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s aid ranked 12th as an aid doner when the amount of aid was compared to the nation's gross national product, the report said. It said that ratio was 0.31 percent, up 0.01 percentage points from 1986. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> was first, having given 1.1 percent of its gross national product in aid. Meanwhile, the government's <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> said it had extended $ 3.9 billion in loans to developing nations in fiscal 1987, up 8 percent from a year earlier. That fiscal year ended March 31, 1988. An <ORGANIZATION> OECF </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the credits included: $ 757 million to <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>; $ 505 million to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>; $ 435 million to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>; $ 284 million to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>; $ 272 million to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>; and $ 213 million to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
