<HEAD>Taiwan's Trade Surplus Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus totaled $ 1.04 billion in September, down 27 percent from the previous month and down 54 percent from the same month a year ago, the government reported Thursday. The Directorate General of Budget, Accounting and Statistics said exports in September totaled $ 4.47 billion, down 22 percent from the previous month, while imports were $ 3.43 billion, a 20 percent decrease from August. The agency said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> registered a total surplus of $ 7.82 billion for the first nine months of this year, down 48 percent from the same period last year. Against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s biggest trading partner, the surplus totaled $ 992.6 million in September, down 22 percent from August Trade officials attributed the decline of imports and exports partly to the four-day Mid-Autumn Festival holiday in September.
