<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Speculation over burgeoning world oil supplies and unsubstantiated rumors about further rifts within <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> have helped push oil futures below the $ 13-a-barrel level. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> plunged 47 cents to settle at $ 12.60 a barrel Wednesday in heavy, hectic trading. Still, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude recovered from its intra-day low of $ 12.28 barrel. In early trading today, it was up another 22 cents at $ 12.82 a barrel. Crude futures prices have not been this low since August 1986. A month ago, the near-term <ORGANIZATION> WTI </ORGANIZATION> contract had settled at $ 14.79. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 1.67 cents to settle at 39.44 cents a gallon, while home heating oil slipped 0.41 cent to 37.76 cents a gallon. Much of the day's selling was technical in nature, analysts said. Oil prices fell sharply on early rumors that <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> had decided to leave the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> General Secretary <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, known as a crafter of compromises, would step down. Prices recovered somewhat when the rumors were denied. <PERSON> Nauman </PERSON> <PERSON> Barakat </PERSON>, vice president of energy investment at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said `` this market has become so rumor-sensitive that even if a story does n't sound credible, there is a violent reaction.'' <PERSON> Barakat </PERSON> said at least some of the rumors were being instigated by floor traders seeking to benefit their own positions. He also said <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> was giving the market a dose of its own `` intensive shock therapy.'' <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the world's largest exporter, has voiced threats that it will continue overproducing unless other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members abide by their production quotas. `` We're in a price war,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an assistant director at <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Unless the Saudis change their policy, the only way oil prices will rise is through technical factors. `` There's no hope on the fundamental front,'' he said. Even before trading began, the market was poised for a selloff with the latest statistics from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The report, which was released after the close of trading Tuesday, showed a higher-than-expected increase in crude oil stocks. The report also showed a sharp increase in refinery runs. `` It just scares people to see the refineries looking like they are going to increase the supply of refined products,'' <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said.
