<HEAD>Congress Moving To Boost Resources To Rescue Thrift Institutions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senate Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said today the next president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must find a solution to the problems plaguing the savings and loan industry or they `` could affect the entire <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. economy.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s comments, on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor, came a day after the government's top thrift industry regulator raised the estimated price tag for cleaning up the industry from $ 31 billion to $ 45 billion or more. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, told his fellow senators that the issue transcends politics. `` The time has come to stop the political finger-pointing,'' he said. `` There is plenty of blame to go around. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, a number of state legislatures, federal regulators and industry management must all share some of the responsibility for the thrift industry's problems,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said `` We should not let politics affect our better judgment. The problems facing the thrift industry are serious. If unaddressed, they could affect the entire <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy,'' he said. On Wednesday, <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates federally chartered S & amp; Ls, argued for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to raise the ceiling on how much it can borrow to bail out ailing thrifts. Just three months ago, Wall had raised his estimate from $ 22 billion to $ 31 billion. Now, he says, the bailout cost is in the range of $ 45 billion to $ 50 billion. Some private analysts put the cost as high as $ 100 billion. But <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said today that more money, by itself, is not the answer. `` It's going to take time to come up with a responsible, workable solution, and, unfortunately, the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> does n't have any left,'' the Republican leader said, urging President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s succesor and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sworn in next January to make finding a solution a top priority The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 29-22 on Wednesday to expand the board's borrowing limit from $ 10.8 billion in bonds to $ 15.8 billion. The move is opposed by the industry, which pays an assessment to retire the 30-year bonds. The panel's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Fernand </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> St </PERSON> <PERSON> Germain </PERSON>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would be `` hard put'' to oppose an expansion of the bank board's borrowing limit, since last summe, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> authorized $ 10.8 billion in borrowing over three years, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> pushed for a higher limit of $ 15 billion. The bank board already has issued $ 3.75 billion in bonds. The Banking Committee bill would permit the bank board to float the remaining amount as soon as needed rather than spreading it over the next two years. So far this year, the bank board has committed $ 20 billion to close or merge 122 troubled thrifts. <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said his agency's resources could cover the newly estimated cost, but only by placing `` an exceedingly heavy burden'' on the industry. Thrift institutions currently pay more than twice as much as their competitors, commercial banks, for deposit insurance and <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said that differential would have to continue over 30 years if his agency did not get help. The head of the industry's largest trade group, the <OR