<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> ended higher, near the day's best levels, Thursday, as trading activity continued at a relatively brisk pace for the second consecutive day. Dealers said the market repeated the pattern of Wednesday's performance, when modest buying by institutions was more than matched by aggressive short-covering by market makers Short-covering is the buying of shares to fulfill agreements to sell them. `` Market makers have been caught a little bit on the hop here and did n't have the stock to meet it,'' said one equity salesman. The Financial Times-Stock Exchane 100-share index rose 12.6 points, or 0.7 percent, to close at 1,838.9, just 2 points below its best level. Volume was 573 million shares, nearly matching Wednesday's relatively healthy 574.5 million shares Consumer-oriented issues were among the market's major gainers as players turned to stocks that had suffered recently due to worries that British interest rates could move yet higher in the near term. Such fears have eased somewhat, with some players cautiously hoping that interest rates might have peaked. Even should bank base lending rates go above their current 12 percent, many players anticipate a bit of a breathing space in the meantime. `` There's no fear at the moment of a sudden hike,'' in rates, a salesman said.
