<FIRST>r f AM-U.S.Competition     10-06 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-U.S. Competition,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Current, Former Secretaries Offer Contrasting Views</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Labor Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> and one of her predecessors offered sharply contrasting opinions Thursday on whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has lost its competitive edge in world trade. `` I'm not sure we're behind,'' Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said at the third annual <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Labor-Management Relations. `` Right now, exports are up and the trade deficit is falling.'' But <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, labor secretary during the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, said that while some economic measures of competitiveness may not indicate a decline, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has fallen behind in productivity and real income levels. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, in a speech to more than 300 business and academic officials, said the next president will have to define a clear set of goals before the country will again become competitive with other countries. `` We have a passive trade policy. They have an active trade policy,'' he said. `` The country with an active trade policy will win because they know where they want to get and how they're going to get there.'' Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, in an interview and an upbeat speech to the group, disagreed and said the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s present programs will get the job done. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, unlike <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and some other Western countries, does not have a centralized economy, so the government can not impose the goals that <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> suggested, Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said. The speakers at the conference agreed that more attention should be paid to improving management systems and the education and services provided to workers. Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said issues such as parental leave should be negotiated between unions and management, rather than imposed by the federal government. `` I'm saddened that they seem to want to push for federal legislation,'' she said. `` If there's federal legislation, then there's less incentive to negotiate.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKersie </PERSON>, an industrial relations professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, said such issues give unions a wedge to organize industries where workers have so far not been interested. `` While unions have seen little recent organizing success, it appears that employees do not appear to be satisfied with the status quo,'' <PERSON> McKersie </PERSON> said. `` The workforce appears to have unsatisfied demands in areas such as pay equity, career development, day care, -LRB- and -RRB- maternity leave.'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, now a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>, said productivity per worker, in and of itself, is not the reason the country has declined relative to <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other economic powers. `` We're four times as productive as the Koreans. The problem is the wage differential is six to one,'' he said. `` So even if we're more productive, they can undercut us with lower wages. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> added that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will never be able to cut wages to the point where they are competitive with the Koreans and should not try to do so. Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said she views education as the key to keeping the workforce competitive. `` Simply put, we have to get serious, together, many of you in this room, about public education,'' she said. `` The fact is that the current pool of applicants for entry-level jobs lacks basic skills such as reading, writing, problem-solving and communication.''
