<FIRST>r f AM-OrangeSqueeze     10-06 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Orange Squeeze,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indictment Of Polk County Citrus Company To Be First Of Many</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fraud indictment of a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus company is the first growing out of a 22-month nationwide investigation of illegal citrus practices involving hundreds of millions of dollars, federal officials said Thursday. `` It was the first indictment, but the investigation is not limited to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Knutter </PERSON>, supervisor of the the <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> fraud group which is coordinating the probe. The lengthy probe, dubbed `` Operation Orange Squeeze,'' is an unprecedented investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> of the citrus industry in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and other citrus-producing states, officals said. A <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> citrus processor, its <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> parent company and two of its former presidents were indicted Tuesday, accused of conspiring to bilk the federal government in a customs rebate scam. <ORGANIZATION> Allsun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Juice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and two former <ORGANIZATION> Allsun </ORGANIZATION> executives, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurley </PERSON>, 57, of <LOCATION> Lakeland </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, 67, of <LOCATION> Ormond </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, were charged with mislabeling export products between 1983 and 1986 in order to collect $ 776,458 in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs rebates. Authorities charge the defendants attempted to cheat the government by labeling almost 2 million gallons of citrus pulpwash as frozen concentrated orange juice in 36 export shipments. Pulpwash is the residual citrus product left after the primary juice claim those rebates for exporting pulpwash, an inferior citrus byproduct, authorities say. Trying to pass the pulpwash off as concentrated orange juice was a fraud, the indictment says. The defendants have so far declined to comment on charges listed in the indictment. Custom laws allow companies 99 percent refund of import duties if products made from imported merchandise are later exported. The rebate also is allowed if the export is produced from a domestic substitute of the same kind and quality as the duty-paid import. Officials say more charges are expected against other exporters. `` Pulpwash may be one of the more fraudulent activities, but we're not limiting the investigation to that,'' <PERSON> Knutter </PERSON> said. In order to track exports, he said, investigators have to trace shipping records and trucking reports involving a number of companies. `` This is just the start,'' said Customs agent <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON>. `` We'll be busy for a while.'' <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON> said investigators discovered a number of citrus concentrate exporters involved in the practice of mislabeling pulpwash as concentrate to get the rebates. When asked if future cases involved as much as hundreds of millions of dollars, <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON> said, `` Overall, that would be a conservative estimate.'' Customs officials said the agency's findings could hurt the credibility of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s citrus industry. `` Operation Orange Squeeze has exposed a situation that could have a devastating effect on the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus industry,'' said Customs agent <PERSON> Bonni </PERSON> <PERSON> Tischler </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>. `` Following natural disasters like the freezes of recent years and the citrus canker infestations, the last thing the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> orange growers and processors need is a company defrauding the government in order to make a few extra dollars.'' Only about 3 percent of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> industry involves citrus concentrate exporting, according to Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Behr </PERSON>, economic research director for the <ORGANIZATION> Citrus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Processors legitimately sell pulpwash to beverage companies who use it to produce diluted citrus drinks. Revenue in the industry totaled more than $ 3 billion last season, he said. Of that amount, about $ 100 million comes from concentrate exports, according to <PERSON> Behr </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
