<HEAD>Rumored Chinese Purchase, Common Market Plans For Exports Spark
Wheat Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A rumored Chinese plan to buy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat and talk that the Common Market plans to raise their wheat export prices triggered a rally in wheat futures prices Thursday at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Expectations that the Chinese may be in the market for wheat also supported wheat prices, analysts said. In other markets, corn prices advanced, soybeans declined, cattle prices were mostly higher, hog prices were mostly lower, frozen pork bellies slid, gold gained, silver was lower and oil prices dipped. Wheat prices hit new contract highs amid continued hope for a Chinese purchase and the rumors of the Common Market's plans, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Higher export prices of Common Market wheat `` would make theirs less competitive and ours more competitive,'' he said Rumors that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> bought a million tons of corn sparked a buying wave in the corn pit, <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said. Soybean prices were pressured by bearish crop estimates from influential private analyst <ORGANIZATION> Sparks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION>, he said. Wheat settled 3 -RCB- cents to 6 -LCB- cents higher, with the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.32 -RCB- a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent to 4 -LCB- cents higher, with December at $ 2.98 a bushel; oats were 2 cents lower to -LCB- cent higher, with December at $ 2.46 \ a bushel; and soybeans were 10 \ cents lower to 2 -RCB- cents higher, with November at $ 8.12 -RCB- a Cattle prices surged at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where traders bought on ideas that supplies will tighten up in the fourth quarter. They seemed to ignore near-term fundamentals of lackluster boxed beef sales and slow feed-yard trade _ both indications that demand is slight, said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Thompson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The hog market fell under the influence of lower cash hog prices, while pork bellies were pressured because of large stocks in storage, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said. Cattle prices settled unchanged to .57 cent higher with October at 72.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .43 cent higher, with October at 81.77 cents a pound; hogs were .38 cent lower to .10 cent higher, with October at 40.02 cents a pound; and pork bellies were .20 cent to .78 cent lower, with February at 48.67 cents a pound. Gold prices at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rallied on expectations that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Labor Department figures to be released Friday would show an improved job picture for September, said analyst <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Inc. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> A slight stabilization in crude oil prices, which have plunged lately, also was considered slightly bullish, he said. Gold was $ 2.70 to $ 3.10 higher, with the contract for delivery in October at $ 403.80 a troy ounce; silver was 1 cent to 1.5 cents lower, with October at $ 6.288 a troy ounce. Oil futures prices settled mostly lower after a rally on mostly technical factors earlier in the session at the <ORGAN