<HEAD>Possible Eastern Sale to TWA Reunites Former Opponents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The reported talks on <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> possibly selling its troubled <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary to rival <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> bring two former bitter foes back together. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, are tenacious financiers who warred over control of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> three years ago. A lot has changed since then, for both men and for the wild world of the deregulated airline business. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> empire went on to acquire Eastern for $ 676 million after his <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> bid failed, apparently has decided that running an unwieldy and fractious airline company is too much trouble. He is believed to be looking to sell parts or all of Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which has been frought with labor difficulty and staggering losses before and since <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> took over. For <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, a well-known takeover strategist who has chased mammoth-sized companies ranging from <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in the past few years, the acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> would make his the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline in terms of revenue passenger miles, an industry measurement of capacity. According to figures of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> trade group, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s combined capacity last year totaled 68.9 billion revenue passenger miles. The leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline last year in capacity was <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, with 66.2 billion revenue passenger miles. Eastern's militant workers, who have persistently characterized <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> as a union buster, have been included in talks with <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> on the possible sale of the airline to him, sources familiar with the situation said Thursday. In an ironic twist, that recalls the move by <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s workers in 1985 to talk with <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> about possibly buying that airline, which <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> was seeking in order to strengthen the operations of his other carrier, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. At that time, <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots and machinists promised <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> hundreds of millions of dollars in labor concessions if he took control, largely because they feared <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> would gut <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> and replace them with lower-paid workers, a strategy <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> had used at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> earlier. After a seesaw struggle that lasted for several months, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> acquired a controlling stake in <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> as part of a broader arrangement to eventually take the airline private, which is expected to be completed soon. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> got about $ 50 million for selling its interest in <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>. Since the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> takeover, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has faced his own labor problems, beginning with a bitter strike by flight attendants in 1986 that left thousands out of work, replaced by new hires at lower pay. Although the strike failed, the flight attendants union has continued to challenge <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> and petitioned the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportion </ORGANIZATION> to review his fitness to run the airline earlier this year. More recently, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has incurred the wrath of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots, who claim he broke promises to them when he initially acquired control of the airline. The pilots have sued him on grounds he is borrowing against the airline's properties without making crucial long-term investments in equipment. `` The solvency of the airline is in question,'' <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> pilots union chief <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashwood </PERSON> said in announcing the lawsuit last month. `` We wo n't stand idly by while <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> strips our airline of assets and keeps it from growing financially stronger, from buying airplanes and from improving service to our passengers because of heavy debt.'' <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has denied the charges of both unions, saying he was `` dismayed'' by their actions.
