<HEAD>Dollar Rises in Quiet Trading; Gold Continues Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar moved narrowly higher Thursday as traders awaited Friday's release of unemployment figures for September. Gold prices also rose. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid of $ 403.50 for a troy ounce of gold, up from $ 400.30 late Wednesday. Dollar trading was very quiet, but some investors adjusted their positions in advance of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s unemployment report, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGroarty </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Discount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Traders were waiting in particular to see what changes there would be in non-farm payroll statistics to be issued with the jobless report, <PERSON> McGroarty </PERSON> said The market expected the non-farm payroll to have increased by about 300,000 to 330,000 workers last month, analysts said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, senior trader at <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the dollar likely would slip if the payroll number fell short of expectations. Traders would interpret an increase in the non-farm payroll as a sign of economic strength. Traders believe the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> is more likely to rein in credit _ moving interest rates higher _ when the economy is robust. The dollar tends to rise along with interest rates. Once the unemployment report has been digested, the market will look forward to next week's release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit figures, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. Overseas trading in the dollar also was slow Thursday in anticipation of Friday's jobless figures. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar slipped 0.18 yen to close at 133.30 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 133.45 yen and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to 133.645 yen from late Wednesday's 133.38. The dollar edged upward against the British pound. It cost $ 1.6935 to buy one pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, cheaper than $ 1.6955 late Wednesday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound was quoted at $ 1.6927, compared with late Wednesday's $ 1.69385. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's prices, included: 1.86585 West German marks, up from 1.86475; 1.5847 Swiss francs, up from 1.5826; 6.3570 French francs, up from 6.3440; 1,391.75 Italian lire, up from 1,3900.00; and 1.20995 Canadian dollars, up from 1.20945. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8641 West German marks, up from 1.8625; 1.5830 Swiss francs, down from 1.5865; 6.3475 French francs, down from 6.3540; 2.1000 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1020; 1,388.75 Italian lire, down from 1,390.475; and 1.2116 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2075. Gold prices closed above $ 400 overseas, catching up to bullion's performance in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Wednesday Gold jumped in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 403.35 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $ 396.00, and it rose in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> to a bid $ 403.90, compared with $ 395.40 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, bullion climbed $ 5.27 to close at a bid $ 405.73. Gold continued to advance on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, closing at $ 403.80 a troy ounce, up from $ 400.80 on Wednesday. Silver bullion prices rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.34 a troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $ 6.19. On the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, silver closed at $ 6.288 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.298 on Wednesday.
