<HEAD>Deere-UAW Contract Includes Pay Raise, Job Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Union workers at <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reportedly would get their first general pay increases since 1981, as well as boosts in retirement benefits and greater job security under terms of a tentative contract agreement. The contract proposal between <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> calls for an average pay raise of 44 cents per hour in the first year of the proposed three-year contract, according to Thursday's edition of the Journal Star of <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> Currently, the 13,500 <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> workers at Deere earn an average $ 15.47 per hour, or $ 32,177 per year based on a 40-hour week. The newspaper, citing unidentified sources within the company and the union, reported that <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> workers would receive bonuses of approximately 3 percent, paid in lump sums, in each of the next two years of the contract. <PERSON> Deere </PERSON>'s union work force has not received a general pay raise since 1981. It has given cost-of-living increases using a formula tied to the consumer price index. Besides wage hikes, the union won a three-step increase in early retirement benefits, the paper reported. In the contract's first year, the monthly pension benefit for those on early retirement would jump from $ 1,205 to $ 1,400. The monthly benefit would reach $ 1,500 in the second year and $ 1,600 in the final year of the pact. The union also claimed significant gains in the contract's job security plan. The proposed contract would guarantee jobs for all workers employed at the time the pact is ratified. The company would only be able to lay off protected employees in times of high inventories, labor disputes, plant closings, sale of a division of the company or `` an act of God.'' Ratification votes are scheduled this weekend at Deere factories and parts warehouses in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The tentative agreement capped a marathon 20-hour bargaining session. <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> negotiated daily for nearly two months before the settlement was announced at 5:08 a.m. Saturday, more than five hours after the current labor contract expired. The new contract would take effect immediately upon ratification and would run through midnight Sept. 30, 1991. If the contract is ratified, <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> and the union will have avoided a repeat of the bitter five-month strike in 1986-87 that ended after 163 days with employees' acceptance of a wage freeze and other concessions. The union hopes to rekindle contract negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> immediately upon ratification of the Deere contract. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> has been meeting with the Peoria-based <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> for two months at a site in <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>.
