<SECOND>AM-Ashland-Spill,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ashland Claims Innocence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Thursday entered a not guilty plea and asked for a jury trial on criminal negligence charges in the Jan. 2 tank collapse that fouled two major rivers with diesel fuel A spokesman for the Kentucky-based company, which publicly admitted errors that figured in the collapse, declined to say whether <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> attorneys are attempting to negotiate a bargain with prosecutors. `` We're having conversations with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney. We're still interested in doing that,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON>. A federal grand jury on Sept. 15 returned a two-count indictment accusing <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> of violating the Clean Water Act and the 1899 Refuse Act. Prosecutors say neither law requires the government to prove the pollution was intentional. If convicted on both counts, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> could be fined $ 400,000 plus double the damage caused by the spill. The spill occurred when a steel tank at the company's <LOCATION> Floreffe </LOCATION> terminal burst as it was being filled for the first time since the World War II-era structure was dismantled near <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and reassembled south of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. An independent study blamed the collapse on a dime-size flaw near one of the welds used in reassembling the tank. Besides failing to obtain all the necessary local permits to erect the tank, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> admitted violating industry standards by not filling the vessel with water to test its strength. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said Jan. 27 that employees responsible for moving the tank were told more than a year earlier about faulty welds in the vessel walls. A memo describing the faults was n't uncovered by senior management until nearly three weeks after the tank collapsed, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> maintains it is unfairly being prosecuted. `` We've spent $ 13 million in reimbursements and cleanup costs,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said. `` We do n't feel that any of our conduct justifies a criminal penalty.'' An estimated 3.8 million gallons of oil gushed from the tank as it crumpled. Most of the oil was contained by a dike, but an estimated 715,000 gallons entered the <LOCATION> Monongahela </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and flowed into the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Tap water service was discontinued to 23,000 suburban <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> residents for a week after the spill, and water supplies for nearly a million other residents in three states along the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> was threatened.
