<HEAD>Mercedes Prices Heading Up Slightly For '89</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROSSE POINTE SHORES, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The formidable price tags on 1989 <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> automobiles will rise a modest 1.7 percent over 1988, and the company is testing a new used-car warranty program, officials said Thursday. Prices for the West German-made luxury cars will range from $ 30,980 for the 190 diesel sedan, to $ 79,840 for the two-door 560SEC. The best-selling car in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Escort </ORGANIZATION>, with a base price of about $ 7,500, less than a tenth of the 560SEC's sticker. <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Krampe </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said he does n't expect any price fluctuations in 1989 because of the exchange rate between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and the West German mark. He said he was happy with the company's sales performance despite slipping a little from last year's level of about 80,000 cars. He said during the past year, <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes </ORGANIZATION> had restructured itself and it's paying off. The luxury car market, of which Mercedes holds a significant share, will continue to grow, <PERSON> Krampe </PERSON> said, and competition in it will increase as <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> introduce their Lexus and Infiniti lines next year. `` The overall luxury market, there is a lot of steam in there,'' <PERSON> Krampe </PERSON> added. But along with holding its volume of new car sales about the same level, Mercedes is looking at improving its used-car operations through a pilot warranty program in 20 dealerships nationwide. `` We want to test how it works on the dealer level, customers and our own administration,'' <PERSON> Krampe </PERSON> said. For cars less than 8 years old and with less than 100,000 miles, the program would offer a 12-month, bumper-to-bumper warranty. The program started a few weeks ago and will be assessed in December, <PERSON> Krampe </PERSON> said. Dealers would set the cost of the warranty. Officials said about 60 percent of the new Mercedes sold are bought by former Mercedes owners. The cars retain 65 to 70 percent of their original value in two years and 40 percent to 45 percent after five years, they added. All of the new'89 Mercedes will be equipped with anti-lock brake systems and driver-side air bags. Some cars will have passenger-side air bags as standard equipment. The average new Mercedes buyer is 40 to 43 years old and comes from a household with an income of about $ 100,000 annually, <PERSON> Krampe </PERSON> said.
