 A <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court has upheld a proxy vote electing new R.P. <ORGANIZATION> Scherer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> board members backed by dissident shareholders who want to sell the gelatin capsule company, <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> said Thursday. <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> attorneys were reviewing the ruling received late Wednesday, and had not decided whether to appeal, company spokeswoman <PERSON> Jayne </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON> said. The decision was hailed by <PERSON> Karla </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>, both children of the company's late founder and members of the board of directors, who lead the shareholder group pressing for the sale of the company. `` Yesterday's decision in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> is the latest in a series of victories for R.P. <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> stockholders, who now are several steps closer than they were a week ago to maximizing their investments through sale of the corporation,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> said in a news release. The <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that upheld the contested election of dissident-backed <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Souris </PERSON> to the board. <PERSON> Karla </PERSON> <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> control a total of about 38 percent of the company's outstanding shares. Mrs. <PERSON> Fink </PERSON>'s estranged husband, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fink </PERSON>, <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>'s president and chief executive officer, and management have opposed a sale of the company. <LOCATION> Souris </LOCATION> was elected in the Aug. 17 proxy vote to replace <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON>, who opposes a sale of 