m </ORGANIZATION> has been seeking around $ 90 million in wage reductions from its flight attendants. The ratification vote is expected to be completed in mid-November. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, which lost $ 88.4 million in the first half of the year, believes it needs about $ 540 million over three years in pay cuts and other concessions to turn itself around. The contract with the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> would have saved the airline about $ 81 million over the next three years, according to both the union and <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>. The airline has imposed $ 35 million in cuts on employees represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union under federal labor rules. The unions representing pilots and flight engineers agreed to cuts totaling about $ 240 million over three years.
