<HEAD>Government Appeals Judge's LTV Pension Ruling</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``When LTV ...'' to CORRECT million
to billion.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on Thursday appealed a federal judge's ruling that the government could not force ailing <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to reassume some $ 3 billion in pension obligations. The <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the government agency which insures pensions for some 40 million workers, filed the appeal with the <ORGANIZATION> 2nd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The appeal seeks to overturn `` as a dangerous precedent'' a ruling last June by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> could not make <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> reassume the pension obligations simply because <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> had signed new contracts restoring previously cut health and welfare benefits. `` The appeals court must decide whether federal insurance should protect retirees or provide corporate welfare to profitable companies,'' said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Utgoff </PERSON>, the agency's executive director. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> terminated three pension plans covering some 100,000 workers and retirees of its steel subsidiary after the company filed for bankruptcy reorganization in 1986, listing some $ 6 billion in liabilities. The biggest of the liabilities _ $ 3 billion _ were the pension plans, which then had assets of just $ 1 billion to cover benefits for some 100,000 <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> workers and retirees. When <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> terminated the pension plans, the federal agency became <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s single biggest creditor, assuming responsibility for the $ 2 billion in uncovered pension liabilities. However, the agency does not insure related health and welfare retirement benefits promised by <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> to its workers. When <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> signed new contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> unions restoring those benefits last year, the agency tried to turn the pension plans back over to the company, saying <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> was taking unfair advantage of the federal insurance program to cut costs and buy labor peace. Sweet ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> had shown `` no factual or legal basis'' that the company had abused the pension insurance program, but said he was willing to reconsider the issue with some additional `` fact finding'' by the agency. <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said Thursday that the agency chose to appeal Sweet's ruling to a higher court rather than seek a new hearing based on the additional fact finding.
</TEXT>
